(1, 'UwNTg2MTI5Njo0NzgyMDoy', 'Description', 'Small plant, about six inches in height, with roots \"half the size of a mans finger\"', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65')
(2, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo0NzgyMDoy', 'Habitat', 'Grows in dry prairies', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 1, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65')
(3, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo0NzgyMDoy', 'Use - Food', 'roots boiled and eaten with sugar. \"keeshikeehaukee is the root of a small plant growing in the dry prairies, about six inches in height. The roots are half the size of a mans finger and grow in a cluster. They are boiled and generally eaten with sugar\"', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65')
(4, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODQxNToy', 'Use - Unknown', 'prairie plants', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(5, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODQxNToy', 'Use - Medicinal', '', 'LeBoullenger 1714-1744', '1714-1744', '', '', 0, 0, 'LeBoullenger 1714-1744')
(6, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODQxNToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'used for medicine: \"I take some of this medicine\"', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca. 1700:021.11, \"makiki8i nini, de cette medecine, jen prend\"')
(7, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODQxNToy', 'Related Info', 'A generic Ojibwe word for medicine called \'maskiki\', the Shawnee word for a leaf is \'msiski\', and the Fox word for blade of grass is \'masiskiwi\'. These references together indicate that a prairie grass blade is probably used for a medicinal purpose by all of these cultural groups', '', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s note')
(8, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NjozODc0NDoy', 'Description', 'Neenasionki\' \"is a tall tree of the southwest of the United States which attains a height of 50 to 80 feet.\" \". . . resembling a pecan tree, with few limbs only, trunk straight, and resembling closely the white oak. It bears nuts and the wood is good for burning.\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria')
(9, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NjozODc0NDoy', 'Habitat', '\"My informant saw it nowhere but around the council-house of the Seneca Indians, Quapaw Reservation, Indian Territory.\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 1, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(10, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NjozODc0NDoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'roots used for medicinal purposes. \". . . the Peoria name . . . means the \"unrecognized one.\" \"The roots are called \"great medicine\" by the untutored natives of western prairies. My informant saw it nowhere but around the council-house of the Seneca Indians, Quapaw Reservation, Indian Territory.\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria')
(11, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NjozODc0NDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'firewood. \"It bears nuts and the wood is good for burning\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria')
(12, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NjozODc0NDoy', 'Related Info', 'Not necessarily the same tree species, but the Peoria account of this \'medicine tree\' by Dunn is reminiscent of a Shawnee account of a tree with impressive medicinal properties, whose fruits produced a pain-numbing effect in humans as powerful as opium', 'Eckert 1967', '1967', '', '', 0, 2, 'Eckert 1967:605, notes, from Galloway, W.A., 1934, Old Chillicothe, Xenia, pp. 281-283')
(13, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1NDI2Nzoy', 'Related Info', 'Peehkateeki\' could refer to any one of a number of prairie dwelling dandelion species, including the dwarf dandelion, Krigia dandelion, (perhaps K. virginica, although it is only listed as growing in sandy places), or one of the false dandelions, Agoseris glauca, or Pyrrhopappus carolinianus', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 2, 'Nomenclature from Gleason and Cronquist, 1991, used, and Small (1903), Coulter (1899) used to narrow down species possibilities. No mention of a prairie dandelion in Bogue (1900) (Gonella\'s note)')
(14, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Habitat', 'Found in abundance in wet prairies', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 1, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:63')
(15, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Use - Food', 'tubers eaten. \"These are found in abundance in the wet prairies throughout the country and are gathered in \"hoeing time\" (June). They are easily boiled and when they wish to change colour the Indians throw into the kettle a few leaves of the soft maple, which turns them black\"', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:63-64')
(16, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Use - Food', 'but refers to adding leaves of soft maple to a batch of boiling wild potatoes to turn them black', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(17, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Use - Food', 'the Miami-Illinois term \'ahpena\' means potatoes, and indicated a number of species growing in the western prairies. \"This \"pomme blance\" as named by the \"coureurs des bois\" look dark and are sweeter than our Irish potatoes. They cook in six hours and are usually called by these Indians nalau\'xki pa<\'nacki\" or nalaaohki ahpena, wild potato', 'em', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'em p 359')
(18, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Use - Food', '\"I found some roots, potatoes, for example digging with a stick etc.\"', 'Gravier 170', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca.1700:291.15, \"j ay trouve des racines, pommes de terre, 8g fouissant avec un boic &c.\"')
(19, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Use - Food', 'tubers cooked. \"waap-\", \"It is easily cooked and is considered very good\", resembling the cultivated potato in appearance and taste, found growing in the low prairies', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', 'may refer to a different species', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65')
(20, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Use - Food', 'tubers boiled in water by a slow fire, and then eaten. :\"That country [lands around Lake Michigan] also produces potatoes, some are as large as an egg, others have the size of one\'s fist, or a little more. They boil these in water by a slow fire during twenty-four hours, when they are thoroughly cooked, you will find in them an excellent flavor, much resembling that of prunes\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 0, 'Perrot 1680-1718, translation from French to English by Blair 1911:117, Perrot\'s description may refer to Psoralea esculenta, Helianthus tuberosa or another species producing sizeable tubers, this ref. also published by Dunn ca. 1900')
(21, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Horticultural Info', 'These wild potatoes are gathered in hoeing time [June]', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:63')
(22, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Related Info', 'The Shawnee collected this plant', 'Clark 1993', '1993', '', '', 0, 2, 'Clark 1993')
(23, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Related Info', 'Dunn noted the terms for potato as ahpeniiki also', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 2, 'Dunn ca. 1900:3786dw, 3787dw, Gatschet ca. 1895:1809')
(24, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Related Info', 'Dunn recorded the following sentence in his word list: \"meeshimi\'narkee peeta\'rweeloa paanarkee [potatoes] misa\'u aupo\'oshee\" which means \"Bring the apples, potatoes, bread ad wood\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 2, 'Dunn ca. 1900:3788dw')
(25, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 'Related Info', 'Topeka means \"a place to find small or wild potatoes\" in the Kaw language, and in the swamp or dry lake near the Shawnee hills exist (location of the Indianola ferry of the past) many wild potatoes grow and are eaten by wild hogs', 'Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 1908', '1908', '', '', 0, 2, 'Aatotankiki myaamiaki 1(2):2, originally from Moore 1908')
(26, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2NzUwOjI=', 'Habitat', 'Found growing out of year-old or more horse manure in horse pasture', 'Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 1, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(27, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2NzUwOjI=', 'Use - Unknown', '', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895, Miami')
(28, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2NzUwOjI=', 'Use - Food', 'picked and eaten. Lots of types picked, mostly the ones that grew in pasture fields where there were horses--the mushrooms growing out of the manure that was at least one year old and had been worked into the ground. There were spring mushrooms and fall mushrooms. The fall mushrooms were the same as the ones that were bought in the store, pink underneath and good tasting [Agaricus sp.]. Some were poisonous so they stuck to eating the ones they knew', 'Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(29, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2NzUwOjI=', 'Use - Food', '\" . . . Godfroy\'s belief was that they did not use poke, mushrooms, or wild lettuce, until they learned to eat them from the whites. He was probably wrong as to this, as the instruction concerning the use of native plants came the other way\"', 'Dunn 1919', '1919', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn 1919')
(30, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MTQxNDoy', 'Use - Unknown', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'unknown source list')
(31, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4NjQ1Nzoy', 'Habitat', 'Found in prairies', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 1, 'Pease 1934:347, Deliette 1721')
(32, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4NjQ1Nzoy', 'Use - Food', 'gathered and stored. \"They also store up onions, as big as Jerusalem artichokes, which they find in the prairies, and which I find better than all the other roots. They are sugary and pleasing to the palate. They are cooked like macopines\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:347, Deliette 1721, \"Elles amassent aussi des oignons gros comme des Topiniamboures, qu\'elles trouvent dans les prairies que je trouve meilleures que toutes les autres Racines, ils sont sucre et font plaisir a manger on les fait cuire comme les Macopines,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(33, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Use - Medicinal', 'root used to cure rattlesnake bite. \". . . they have an admirable root, which, as soon as it is applied to the wound, softens the swelling so that by the next day one is cured. This root is found in the prairies and is shaped like an onion. The stem grows two feet high, the leaves are very narrow and somewhat resemble those of the sumac. It forms large buds in which the seed is lodged. I have made a point of hunting for it in this country, but have never been able to find any. I have been told that they had still another kind, but I have not become acquainted with it.\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:372, Deliette 1721, \"qu\'ils ont d\'une Racine admirable, sitot qu\'on en a mis sur la playe elle fait amolir L\'enflure et le Lendemain on est guery, cette Racine se trouve dans Les prairies et est faitte comme unoignon,La tige vient de deux pieds de deux pieds de haut, La feuille fort etroitte qui aproche celle des Vinaigriers, Il se forme de gros Boutons dans quoy est la graine, je me suis attachez a en chercher dans ce pays mais je n\'en ay jamais pu trouver, on ma dit qu\'il y en avoit encore d\'une autre sorte, mais je ne la connois point,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(34, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Use - Food', '\"sweet roots\" and vegetables were usually cultivated or gathered in large quantities. Mentioned by Trowbridge in the context of wedding gifts, a series of reciprocities, where sweet roots and vegetables being given by the older women in-laws of the bride in return for the meat given by the bride\'s brother', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:43')
(35, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Use - Medicinal', 'emetics. \"The most common medicines are emetics . . . composed of roots, which are pounded and mixed with water.\" \"There are many roots and weeds used by them for emetics, the most common of which is the root of the Buckeye.\"', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:48')
(36, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Use - Medicinal', 'treatment for rheumatism is to apply pounded roots and weeds with a bandage to affected areas.\"', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:48')
(37, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Use - Medicinal', 'a kind of homeopathic medicine using roots. Some medicine men used the same root that \'conveys\' the disease to cure it.\"', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:49')
(38, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Use - Medicinal', 'special medicine men could cure a patient of a disease originating from a poison. The medicine man coughs up a white substance, places it in his hand. If it goes through the medicine man\'s hand, the patient will die, if it does not, he will live. Before this is known, the medicine man give the patient a small supply of roots and tells him to have good faith, then leaves.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:55')
(39, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Use - Food', 'keeshikeehaukee is a small plant growing in the dry prairies, and is about six inches in height, with small roots about an inch long growing in a cluster. These are boiled and eaten with sugar.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65')
(40, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Use - Food', 'waukeepaaneekee is a plant growing in the bottom lands that is similar to the onion in root and shape. It is boiled 12 hours before eaten. It is not a popular food because it causes constipation.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65')
(41, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Horticultural Info', 'Village location sometimes was chosen for its nearness to an abundance of root crops', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:350, Deliette 1721, \"y en a une si grande quantite dans la Riviere et principalement dans le Lac au bout duquel les Illiois sont Etablis du coste du nord a cause de la quantite de Racine qu\'il,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(42, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Horticultural Info', 'A digging stick was used for gathering roots or potatoes. \"I have found some roots, potatoes, for example digging with a stick etc.\"', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca.1700:291.15, \"nimic8ah8aki,\" \"j ay trouve des racines, pommes de terre, 8g fouissant avec un bois &c,\" translation from French to English by Masthay')
(43, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 'Horticultural Info', 'The Old Illinois term \'nimic8picahan\' translates to modern French as \"je l ay cherche dans l eau avec un baston et je la ay trouve,\" meaning \"I looked for it in the water with a stick and I found it\".', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', 'Since this directly follows the entry for macopines, it proably refers to a harvesting methods of this, and other edible aquatic roots (Gonella\'s note);', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca.1700:292.25')
(44, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4MzQ4OjI=', 'Use - Food', 'eaten as greens', 'Rafert 1978', '1978', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Swan Hunter and Eva Bossley, Rafert 1978')
(45, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4MzQ4OjI=', 'Related Info', 'Melipikan is indian name for the plant', 'Rafert 1978', '1978', '', '', 0, 2, 'Interview with Swan Hunter and Eva Bossley, Rafert 1978')
(46, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4MzQ4OjI=', 'Related Info', 'Possibly related to this word: \'pekan\' is a French-Canadian word for an animal called a Fisher, Mustela pennanti, similar to a Marten or Mink. Its fur was highly sought after by fur trappers', 'Blair 1911', '1911', '', '', 0, 2, 'Blair 1911:113')
(47, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'funeral. Timber from an old canoe was used to laid dead body on and to act as walls to hold the earth in place along the sides of the graves. Favorite items were placed with the body in the grave, regardless of status, including a little kettle or pot, tobacco, corn, a calumet, bow and arrows. A forked stick is placed a foot from the deceased head and feet and stakes are set around to keep the animals out', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:357-358, Deliette 1721, \"Ils couppent ordinairement deux fourches de dix pieds et un travers creusent la terre de la Longueur de la personne, et un peu plus Large mettent une planche de leurs Vieux Canots ou pirogues et posent le mort dedans en mettant une a chaque coste . . . Une petite chaudiere ou pot de terre, Environ une jointee de Bled, un Caumet, une pincee de Tabac un arc et des fleches, et Ensuite ils replantent une de ces fourches a un pied de ses pieds et l\'autre a la meme distance de sa teste, Le travers dessus et ensuitent posent leurs pieux en des d\'asne de chaque coste et ont le soin de bien fermer les bouts de maniere que les animequx n\'y puissent entrer,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(48, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'funeral. Deceased placed into coffin-like enclosures made of bark. Prior to the burial there was singing and danced for about 24 hours, and dancers had gourd rattles. After this 24 hour period, the body was buried with \"indian wheat\" (Joutel) and a pot to cook it in so the person would not be hungry during the journey', 'Myaamiaki 2000', '2000', '', '', 0, 0, 'Joutel\'s journal of LaSalle\'s last voyage down the Mississippi (?), Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 3(1):3, 2000')
(49, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'funeral. Body buried in the halves of a hollowed out tree, one half held the body, the other was put on top. The two halves were bound together with rope or anchored to the ground with crosspieces', 'Robertson 1879', '1879', '', '', 0, 0, 'Robertson 1879, Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 3(1):3, 2000')
(50, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'funeral. \"If the deceased has been a chief of war parties that have brought in prisoners they plant a tree forty or fifty feet long, which several men go to fetch at the request of the relatives, who give a feast. From this tree they peel the bark and color it with the shades of red and black and make pictures of the chief and the prisoners he has taken, tie a bundle of small logs representing as many persons as he has killed, which they also fasten to the stake and then they plant it beside the tomb\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:357-358, Deliette 1721, \"Si c\'est un chef de partis, qui ayent amene des prisonniers, ils plantent une arbres que plusrs. Hommes vont chercher sur la demande que leur en font les parents par un festin de quarente ou cinqte. Pieds de long, duquel ils levent l\'ecorce, Et y font des nuances de Rouge et de noir et dessinent son portraits, et les prissonniers qu\'il amene Lie un tas de Buchettes d\'autant de personnes qu\'il a tue qu\'il attachent encore au poteau et ensuitte ils le plantent a coste du tombeau,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(51, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'war death song. Honoring those killed in battle after victory. \"These [warriors] sing their death song, holding in one hand a stick ten or twelve feet long, filled with feathers from all the kinds of birds that the warriors killed on the road\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:383, Deliette 1721, \"qui chantent leurs chansons de mort, ayant dans une main un baston de dix ou douze pieds de Long, rempli de plumes de toutes les sortes d\'oyseaux que les guerriers ont Tuez dans la Route,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(52, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'funeral. Story about a coffin made for a soldier that died on the Peoria reservation. \"They marked a hickory tree at the head of the grave with marks three feet from the ground and a chinquapin oak at the foot of the grave near the ground.\"', 'Burns 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938')
(53, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'funeral. \"Four persons, not related to the deceased are appointed by the relatives to carry the body to the grave. This is prepared by digging to the depth of two and a half or three feet, and is lined with planks or bark (or when near the whites the body is put in a coffin.). The corpse is followed to the grave by the near relatives first, who are joined by those more distant and by the friends of the deceased.\"', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:30')
(54, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'funeral. It was customary, for deceased male or females, to put into the grave some meat, a little bark-cup of water at the feet, and his rifle or her silver, or other valuables.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:33')
(55, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'stick used in playing a ball game called Pekitehomingk', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:53')
(56, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'Sansawingee is a game played with a wooden bowl, and six plumb stones, one side black and the other white. Very popular, and much betting is involved, sometimes losing all they have, including horses and guns.', 'Trowbridge 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1938:60')
(57, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'Pekitarhunar Pukwauhkoan is a game played with a wooden ball, perforated with two holes to make it sing as it flies through the air. As many as 600 people can play at a time in a field delimited by four poles upon which hang the articles at stake in the betting.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:62')
(58, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'Marmeeshauhkwauhenar is a game which uses a small wooden ball or stick which is thrown at a piece of brass or tin suspended from a very tall pole by a string.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:63')
(59, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'a little white flag is placed at the grave of a deceased person for three days, because tradition says that it takes three days for the spirit to reach the place it\'s going', 'Kohn 1997', '1997', '', '', 0, 0, 'Kohn 1997, Floyd E. Leonard')
(60, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'wooden stick and board containing a \"black berry\" [hole] is used with dry, very fine grass crushed and used as kindling to start a fire. \"One of the pieces of wood which they use to make a fire is of white cedar, which is the most combustible, a foot long more or less, according as they choose to make it, and as thick as two fingers. On one side, on the very edge, they make little holes, in which they make a notch. They put this bit of wood on some rotten wood or on some grass, dry and very fine, after taking care to crush it thoroughly in their hands. The other piece of wood is as thick as the little finger; it is a bit of a wood that has a black berry, which we call morette. When this wood is green it is very soft, and it is proportionately hard when it is dry. They shape the end to the size of the holes in the other piece of wood, into one of which they insert it, and by turning it in their hands without ceasing, they produce a sort of powder from which, after a very short time, one sees smoke issue, which shortly is converted into flame. This coming through the notch of which I have just spoken, falls on the rotten wood or dry grass, which is ignited\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:317-318, Deliette 1721; \"un de ces morceaux don’t on se sert pour faire du feu est de Cedre blanc qui est le plus combustible d\'un pied plus ou moins de long, selon celle qui\'ils veulent luy donner, de la largeur de deux doigts, ils font d\'un coste tout sur le bord de petits trous, ou ils font une coche, ils mettent ce morceau de bois sur du bois poury, ou sur de l\'herbe bien seche et bien fine, apres qu\'ils ont eu le soin de la bien ecraser dans leurs mains, l\'autre morceau de bois est gros comme le petit doigt, c\'est un brin d\'un bois qui rapporte une graine noire, que nous appellons de la morette, quand ce bois est vert il est fort foible, et a proportion dur quand il est sec, ils amenuisent le bout de la grosseur des Troux de l\'autre morceau de bois, dans un desquels ils le mettent, et en le tournant dans leurs mains sans relache, ils se fait une maniere de poussiere don’t on voit en tres peu de temps comme j\'ay deja dit, sortir de la fumee, et ensuite se convertir en feu, cela coulant par cette coche don’t je viens de parler, tombe sur ce bois pouris ou herbe seche qui se convertit en feu,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(61, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'three poles of wood were cut to make a large tripod from which they hung a big kettle for cooking', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:308-309, Deliette 1721; \"le bois couper 3. perches don’t ils firent un grand Tripied, auquel, auquel ils pendirent une grande Chaudiere qu\'ils emplirent pleine d\'eau et s\'assirent autour du feu qu\'ils avoient fait dessous,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(62, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'firewood. \"He said that he was coming uup with a large number of engages, and that I [Deliette] should therefore sound the Illinois regarding abandonment of their village, for which they had shown a desire because their firewood was so remote and because it was difficult to get water upon the rock if they were attacked by the enemy\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:326-327, Deliette 1721; \"qu\'il montoit avec quantitez d\'engagez, ainsy que je sondassent L\'esprit des Illinois touchant l\'abandon qu\'il luy avoient temoigne avoir envie de faire de leur Village, a cause de l\'eloignement du Bis de chauffage, et de la difficulte qu\'il y avoit d\'avoir de l\'eau de dessus le Rocher, si l\'on etoit attaque de l\'ennemy,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(63, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'firewood. \" . . . it is always the women who supply the cabins and the firewood\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:332, Deliette 1721; \"ce sont toujours les femmes qui font les Cabanes et le bois de chaufage,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(64, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'firewood used in cooking white water lily roots, macopines, in an underground oven with grass and bark protecting the roots', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:346, Deliette 1721, \"Elles Jettent dedans quantite de Bois dans lequel elles mettent le feu,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(65, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'funeral. \"If the dead man is a warrior who has loved the dance very much, the relatives assemble in his cabin to see what they can give. They count how many villages they represent and agree on the thing as best they can in order that none may be dissatisfied. They plant for this purpose three or four forks, according to the amount of merchandise there is to give, [in honor of the deceased], and fix crosspieces on which they hang several kettles, guns, and hatchets. They send word to the chiefs of each village to send their warriors to dance for such a one who is dead in order that he may go to enjoy the bliss which all men will one day enjoy.\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:359, Deliette 1721; \"Si ce\'st un guerriers qui a aimez beaucoup les danses, les parens s\'assemblent dans la Cabane du deffunt et voyent ce qu\'ils peuvent donner ils comptent les Villages, qu\'ils sont et conviennent de la chose de la meilleure maniere qui leur est possible, afin qu\'il n\'y aye point de mecontent ils plantent pour cela trois ou quatre fouches selon la quantite de marchandises qu\'il a a donner et y mettent desTravers sur quoy ils pendent plusieurs chaudieres, fusils haches et envoyent Chez les chefs de chaque village dire d\'envoyer danser leurs Guerriers pour un tel qui est mort affin qu\'il aille Jouir des delices que tous les hommes jouiront un Jour,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(66, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'pieces of wood and Indian corn husks, and stones were thrown at the Jesuit fathers when they announced mass and catechisms', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:362, Deliette 1721, \"Les morceaux de bois, costons de bled d\'inde, et meme les pierres qu\'on leurs jettent quelquefois,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(67, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'singing the calumet to other nations. Messengers are sent ahead as they approach another nation, to announce their arrival. These messengers are of \"good cheer\" and go to the residence of the song recipient and sing for four nights consecutively, all night, then they make a scaffold and place him on it and beat drums and shake their chichicoyas and sing all day long, pushing him back and forth as an honoring. A post is planted as a place to recite this man\'s exploits and then gifts are given.\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:389-391, Deliette 1721; \"Je crois qu\'il est bon que je fasse encore Le Detail de la maniere qu\'ils font quand ils veulent chanter Le Calumet a quelques Nations. A Deux Lieues du Village ou ils vont ils envoyent quelques uns de Leurs gens Les plus Connus dire Leurs arrivees combien ils sont et a qui ils Le Viennent chanter on envoye au devant deux, avec ordre de Leur dire Combien ils doivent Loger d\'hommes dans Le Village des Peourias, Combien dans Celuy des Kaskaskias et ainsi des autres, Et si celuy a qui ces Etrangers ont dessein de donner Le Calumet est en Etat de Le recevoir, car tout glorieux que sont ces sauvages, ils ne sont point honteux de dire quand ils sont gueux, et a qui il faut qu\'ils Le chantent. La bonne chere ne Leur manque pas a leur arrivee, apres quoy le mesme Soir Ils s\'en vont dans la Cabanne de celuy a qui ls doivent donner Le Calumet, et chantent Jusqu\'au Jour, ce qu\'ils font pendt. quatre nuits consecutives, apres quoy ils font des Echaffauts dehors si il fait beau temps Et Vont chercher L\'homme ou ses femmes a qui ils chantent Le Calumet, et le montent sur cet Echaffaut, ils se mettent tous a Coste de Luy, Battent du Tambour, secouent Leur Chichicoya Et chantent toute La Journee. Deux Le poussent doucement L\'un a L\'autre marques d\'autant plus grande de L\'honeur qu\'ils Luy font, pendant tout ce temps, tout Le monde vient fraper a un poteau qu\'on a plante Exprest, dire ses prouesses, et apres jettent plus ou moins selon la faculte d\'un chacun, L\'honeur que merite celuy a qui ils chantent Le Calumet, Et la Cas qu\'ils en font,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(68, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'still, line fishing done with a lure that is made with a hard and pointed piece of wood hidden inside half a fish, at the end of a line. The wood is inserted in a way that the fish does not see it. \"By this means they take many trout\"', 'Raudot 1904', '1904', '', '', 0, 0, 'Raudot, 1904:Letter 41; secondary source for Deliette 1721')
(69, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'the calumet for peace was made from a polished red stone, and a hollowed out stick, two feet long about 2-3 cm diameter, and adorned with heads, necks, and large red and green feathers of beautiful birds. \"It [calumet for peace] is fashioned from a red stone, polished like marble, and bored in such a manner that one end serves as a receptacle for the tobacco, while the other fits into the stem; this is a stick two feet long, as thick as an ordinary cane, and bored through the middle. It is ornamented with the heads and necks of various birds, whose plumage is very beautiful. To these they also add large feathers, --red, green, and other colors,--wherewith the whole is adorned. They have a great regard for it, because they look uponit as the calumet of the Sun; and, in fact, they offer it to the latter to smoke when they wish to obtain a calm, or rain, or fine weather\"', 'Marquette 1673', '1673', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1673, from Thwaites 1966:131; \"Il est compose d\'une pierre rouge polie comme du marbre et percee d\'une telle facon qu\'un bout sert a recevoir le tabac et l\'autre s\'enclave dans le manche, qui est un baston de deux pieds de long, gros comme une canne ordinaire et perce par le milieu il est embelly de la teste et du col de divers oiseaux, don’t le plumage est tres beau ils y ajoutent aussi de grandes plumes rouges, vertes et d\'autres couleurs, don’t il est tout empanache; ils enfont estat particulierement, parcequ\'ils le regardent comme le calumet du Soleil; et de fait, els le luy presentent pour fumer quand ils veulent obtenir du calme, ou de la pluye, ou du beau temps,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites')
(70, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'structure made from wooden poles for protection from mosquitos. \"This is what the savages of this quarter do to protect themselves against them [mosquitos]. They erect a scaffolding, the floor of which consists only of poles, so that it is open to the air in order that the smoke of the fire made underneat may pass through, and drive away those little creatures, which cannot endure it; the savages lie down upon the poles, over which bark is spread to keep off rain\"', 'Marquette 1673', '1673', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1673, from Thwaites 1966:147; \"Voicy ce que font les sauvages de ces quartiers pour s\'en deffendre; ils elevent un eschaffault don’t le plancher n\'est fait que de perches, et par consequent est perce a jour affinque la fumee du feu qu\'ils font dessous passe au travers et chasse ces petitz animaux quui ne la peuvent supporter, on se couche sur les perches au dessus desquelles sont des escorces estendues contre la pluye,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites')
(71, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'dishes made of wood. \"Their dishes are of wood; but their spoons are made of the bones of the skull of wild-oxen, which they cut so as to make them very convenient to eat their Sagamittee\"', 'Thwaites 1903', '1903', '', '', 0, 0, 'Thwaites 1903:652, from Marquette 1673:210')
(72, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'wooden poles used to fasten tall grass to roof of corn drying shed. \"I think she said when they first come from Indiana there was a tall grass that they covered their dry sheds with . . . To dry their corn or somethin\' like that. They tied it down with poles. Now that\'s amazing to me how that would turn [repel] water\"', 'Carver 1968', '1968', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Rose Carver by J.W. Tyner, Miami, OK, 9/9/1968, in MTO Archives')
(73, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'used to build bridges. \"wood put in balance, unstable/unsteady bridge\"', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca.1700:321.26, \"nanamac8issen8i\", \"bois mis en equilibre, pont mal assure,\" translation from French to English by Masthay000')
(74, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'wood ashes thrown into a wound, by Fox Squirrel, to heal', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895, from the traditional story Wissakatchaka told by Elizabeth Vallier, Miami speaker, with help of Sarah Wadsworth')
(75, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'there are 19 Miami items made in part or whole of wood, including doctor\'s cupping horn, stirring paddle, ladle, cradleboard, dice bowls, bow and arrows, moccasin awl handle, pipestem, war club, and human figures, all housed at the National Museum of the American Indian, Washington D.C.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'see attachment: NMAI items')
(76, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'there are 3 Miami items made in part of whole of wood, and four more that are probably composed of wood at the Cranbrook Institute in Michigan. Items include a arrows, a bowl, bows, axe, hair tie board and spoon (see attachment Cranbrook items); 30. MATERIAL: there are a number of Miami items made from wood, including a wooden comb, and sticks, housed at the Glen Black Laboratory in Indiana', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'NAGPRA Inventory')
(77, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material/Customs', 'a bow was retrieved from Little Turtle\'s grave and is housed at the Allen County Historical Society, in Fort Wayne, Indiana', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'MTO files')
(78, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'a wooden pestle, thought to be Miami, is housed at the American Museum of Natural History in New York City', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Cat#50/763')
(79, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'cradleboard made from wood. \"The care which the mothers take of their children, whilst they are still in the cradle is beyond all expression, and proves in a very sensible manner, that we often spoil all, by the reflections which we add to the dictates of simple nature. They never leave them, they carry them every where about with them; and even when theya re ready to sink under the burthen with which they load themselves, the cradle of the child is held for nothing; and one would even think, that this additional weight were an ease to them and rendered them more agile. Nothing can be neater than these cradles in which the child lies as commodiously and softly as possible. But the infant is only made fast from the middle downwards: so that when the cradle is upright, the little creatures have their head and the half of the body hanging down; . . . This posture rendering the body supple and they are in fact of a port and stature . . .\"', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:109-110, from Kellogg 1923:102')
(80, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'small cups and other utensils made from wood', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761-125, from Kellogg 1923:116')
(81, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'posts to build platform for burning prisoners. \"They begin with stripping the sufferer stark naked; they fix two posts in the ground, to which they make fast two cross piees, one two foot from the ground, and the other six or seven feet higher, and this is what they call a square. They cause the person who is to suffer to mount the first cross piece, to which they tie his feet at some distance from each other; they afterwards bind his hands to the two angles formed by the upper cross-piece, and iin this posture they burn him in all the different parts of his body\"', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1683-1761:203, from Kellogg 1923:188')
(82, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'a wooden scaffolding with roof and floor is erected to provide shade on hot days. \"They erect a scaffolding, the floor of which consists only of poles, so that it is open to the air in order that the smoke of the fire made underneath may pass through, and drive away those little creatures [mosquitos], which cannot endure it; the savages lie down upon the poles, over which the bark is spread to keep off rain. These scaffoldings also serve them as a protection against The excessive and Unbearable heat of this country, for they lie in the shade, on the floor below, and thus protect themselves against the sun\'s rays, enjoying the cool breeze that circulates freely through the scaffolding\"', 'Marquette 1674', '1674', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:360')
(83, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'in historic times, Miami fishermen made a platform on the front of a fishing boat where a fire was built to serve as a torch for night fishing', 'Rafert 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:35; 2ndy source, original unknown')
(84, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'pigeon trap made from a wooden frame with bark nets', 'Rafert 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:74-75; 2ndy source, either heard or read by Lamoine, original source unknown')
(85, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'old-style quail traps made with a hole and about twenty forked sticks, corn used as bait in the hole', 'Rafert 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:78-79')
(86, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'wolf trap made by Julius, \"Zeb\" Bundy (1874-1930, AKA Julius Mongosa), step-son of John Bundy, using peeled poles. \"Now, this Bundy trapped sheep killing dogs for a doctor one time. He peeled poles, he cut poles and peeled \'em, made a pen about six by ten, something like that, and he started building up like a log house--he notched \'em, and put one on top of eachother. He could\'ve nailed \'em, but I think he notched them. And each layer of poles was set in just a little bit, so that the walls wasn\'t straight up and down, they come slightly to a point. The entrance up at the top wasn\'t near as wide as down below. Then he put bait downin there, in his case he used sheep, probably. They also used a little bit of axle grease on top of it, it\'d be a hard oil today, just a little bit of it. And these wolves circled round and round there, and one\'d get to that (trap), and they\'re easy to climb up on there and jump down in there. But when they went to get back out, they\'d jump up, and they had no place for the hind feet to go, and they swung under like my dog out there, and they (couldn\'t) jump out of there. They swung under like that, and there they were, and then you could shoot \'em with bow and arrow, or whatever, see\"', 'Rafert 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:82-83')
(87, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'wooden maces used in war. \"Besides the bow, they use in war a kind of short pike, and wooden maces\"', 'Membre 1680-1681', '1680-1681', '', '', 0, 0, 'Membre 1680-1681 regarding La Salle, from Shea 1903:155')
(88, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Use - Technology', 'firewood was plentiful. \"The Illiinois and their neighbors have no lack of wood for drying meat . . .\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 0, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:124')
(89, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Horticultural Info', '\"In the spring, when the nation returns from its winter sojourn, which is at the end of March, or at the beginning of April, they busy themselves gathering wood so as to be able to do their planting at the beginning of May without interruption, for, although in this country the snow is not over four fingers deep and does not lie on the ground a week, and although the rivers are all open at the beginning of March, there are cold spells in May as severe as those of winter.\" (); 2. (); 3. ();', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:339, Deliette 1721, \"le printemps que la nation revient de L\'hivernement qui est a la fin de mars ou au commencementd\'avril, elles s\'occupent a amasser du bois pour pouvoir faire leur semences au commencement de may sans ce detourner, car quoy que dans ce pays la, il n\'y ait pas plus de quatre doigts de neige que meme elle ne dure pas huit jours sur la terre, et que les Rivieres soient toutes deprises au commencement de mars il vient que d\'estre au mois de may, des froids qui sont aussy rudes qu\'en hiver,\" translation from French to English by pease')
(90, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Horticultural Info', 'The Miami-Illinois term \"kipinhsi\" means to cut wood or brush', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:876')
(91, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Horticultural Info', 'The Miami-Illinois phrase \"nila sakusamani kipintha\" means \'I burn down the bushes\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:2022')
(92, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'The women are in charge of cutitng the wood with an axe, carrying it to the lodge, making the fire and cooking the food', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 2, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:46')
(93, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Charlevoix notes a procedure by which the Potawatomi (\"Outagamies\") determined the fate of prisoner. \"Some time ago, a Frenchman having been taken by the Outagamies, these barbarians held a council on their march to determine what they should do with him. The result of their deliberation was to throw a stick upon a tree, and if it remained there to burn the prisoner, but not to throw it above a certain number of times. Happily for the captive, the stick fell always to the ground, though the tree was extremely bushy\"', 'Charlevoix 1683-1761', '1683-1761', '', '', 0, 2, 'Charlevoix 1683-1761:204, from Kellogg 1923:189')
(94, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Perrot described the creation story of Algonquians, including a large raft made of wood, carrying all the animals that existed at the time of creation. \"They believe that before the earth was created there was nothing but water, that upon this vast extent of water floated a great wooden raft, upon which were all the animals, of various kinds, which exist on earth, and the chief of these, they say, was the Great Hare\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:31-32')
(95, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Perrot described the making of bow and arrow by the first men, in the creation story, using wood, bark and nettle cordage. \"These first men, I say, whom hunger had weakened, inspired by the Great Hare with an intuitive idea, broke off a branch from a small tree, made a cord with the fibers of the nettle, scraped the bark from a piece of a bough with a sharp stone, and armed its end with another sharp stone, to serve them as an arrow, and thus they formed a bow [and arrows] with which they killed small birds\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:38')
(96, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Perrot described the use of \'soft wood\' for making fires, in the Algonquian creation story. \". . .they tried to make fire, in order to cook their meat, and, trying to get it, they took for that purpose hard wood, but without success, and [finally] they used softer wood, which yielded them fire\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:38')
(97, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Algonquian women, in general, were responsible for gathering firewood and making bark dishes. The men made the wooden dishes. \"The obligations of women are to . . . furnish firewood . . . They apply themselves to fashioning dishes of bark, and their husbands make the wooden dishes\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:75-76')
(98, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Algonquians use a light piece of wood to make a cradleboard', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:77')
(99, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Algonquians use of wooden scaffolds on which to place the deceased', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:89')
(100, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Algonquians play a game called crosse, played with a wooden ball and racket with a netted end, like a tennis racket. \"There is among them a certain game, called crosse, which has much likenes to our game of long tennis . . . You will see them all equipped with the crosse--which is a light club, having at one end a broad flat part that is netted like a racket, the ball that they use in playing is of wood, and shaped very nearly like a turkey\'s egg\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:93')
(101, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Algonquians use a wooden bowl in the dice game. \"The savages have also a certain game of dice,in which the dice-box is a wooden dish, quite round, empty, and very smooth on both sides\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, fro Blair 1911:101')
(102, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Father Gravier listed the term \"katookwakami?i\" for the wood of an unknown tree and \"cat8c8acamina\" for the fruit of an unknown tree\" but it is unclear whether these terms are to indicate ANY unknown wood of fruit, or one particular tree that was unknown to the speaker', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gravier ca. 1700:106.08,106.07')
(103, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 'Related Info', 'The Miami term \"pakianakgi\" or \"pa\'kianakki\", mean the limb of a tree or bush', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1767; Dunn ca. 1900:3111')
(104, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Material', 'bark peeled for unknown purpose [reason not noted, but this was a buffalo hunting camp and their actions were probably related to making camp during the buffalo hunt]', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:313, Deliette 1721, \"plusrs. feemes qui estoient aux Environs a lever des ecorces vinrent au coup de fusil,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(105, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Material', '\"They use the same term for bark boards, and two of these apacoyas, one on top of the other, protect one from the rain as well as the best blanket. These are the cabins which they use in autumn and winter, even if they leave their canoes, the women carry these on their backs', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:340-341, Deliette 1721, \"ils disent de mesme pour des planches escorces, et deux de ces apacoya L\'un sur l\'autre, metent aussi bien a la pluye que la meilleure couverture, se sont les Cabanes don\'t ils se servent l\'automne et l\'hiver, quoy quils quittent leurs pirogues, les femmes les portent sur leurs dos,\"translation from French to English by Pease')
(106, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Food', 'used in cooking macopines (white water lily rhizome) in a pit, roots placed on aquatic grass which was laid over hot rocks in a pit, then roots covered with dry grass and bark', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:346, Deliette 1721, \"chaque Cabanes met ses Racines en un Endroit les couvrent d\'herbes seches et des Ecorces par dessus et ensuite de la terre,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(107, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Customs', 'funeral. \"If the deceased has been a chief of war parties that have brought in prisoners they plant a tree forty or fifty feet long, which several men go to fetch at the request of the relatives, who give a feast. From this tree they peel the bark and color it with the shades of red and black and make pictures of the chief and the prisoners he has taken, tie a bundle of small logs representing as many persons as he has killed, which they also fasten to the stake and then they plant it beside the tomb\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:358, Deliette 1721, \"Si c\'est un chef de partis, qui ayent amene des prisonniers, ils plantent une arbres que plusrs. Hommes vont chercer sur la demande que leur en font les parents par un festin de quarente ou cinqte. pieds de long, duquel ils levent l\'ecorce, Et y font des nuances de Rouge et de noir et dessinent son portraits, et les prissoniers qu\'il a amene Lie un tas de Buchettes d\'autant de personnes qu\'il a tue qu\'il attachent encore au poteau et ensuitte ils le plantent a coste du tombeau,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(108, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Material', 'shingles made of bark for the houses, fastened to rafters by wooden pins', 'Burns 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938')
(109, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Material', 'spring shelter made of logs covered with bark. \"The respective bands assemble together in the spring at their several ordinary places of resort, where some have rude cabins, made of small logs, covered with bark, but, more commonly, some poles stuck in the ground and tied together with pliant slips of bark, and covered with large sheets of bark, or a kind of mats made of flags\"', 'Dillon 1859', '1859', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dillon 1859:16-17, from a letter written by an Indian Agent, Benjamin F. Stickney to Thomas L. McKinley, Superintendent of Indian Affairs, 8/27/1817')
(110, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Technology', 'bark used as a hand-held torch. Trowbridge describes its use in courtship, where a young man would go secretly into the lodge of the parents of the girl of his interest, using a bark torch for light', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:41')
(111, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Material', 'Paapaamootekutauwee is a game of shooting where a ball of bark is thrown in the air and shot at with an arrow. Betting is involved.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:62')
(112, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Material', 'bark used for summer hunting cabins. \"The women had thrown down their packs and had run, each with an axe, into the woods to cut poles and to peel bark for their summer hunting cabin. As for the kind they use during their winter sojourn, they always carry these along; they are similar to those which they have in summer . . .\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:308, Deliette 1721; \"Les femmes avoient jette leur paquet bas, et avoient courrus avec chacune une hache dans le Bois couper des perches et lever des Ecorces pour leur leur Cabanne de Chasse d\'Ete, pour celle qu\'ils ont dans leur hivernement, ils les portent toujours avec eux; Et sont pareilles a celles qu\'ils ont dans leur Ete,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(113, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Technology', 'structure made from bark and wooden poles for protection from mosquitos. \"This is what the savages of this quarter do to protect themselves against them [mosquitos]. They erect a scaffolding, the floor of which consists only of poles, so that it is open to the air in order that the smoke of the fire made underneat may pass through, and drive away those little creatures, which cannot endure it; the savages lie down upon the poles, over which bark is spread to keep off rain\"', 'Thwaites 1966', '1966', '', '', 0, 0, 'Thwaites 1966 (reprint from 1900):147, Marquette 1673; \"Voicy ce que font les sauvages de ces quartiers pour s\'en deffendre; ils elevent un eschaffault don’t le plancher n\'est fait que de perches, et par consequent est perce a jour affinque la fumee du feu qu\'ils font dessous passe au travers et chasse ces petitz animaux quui ne la peuvent supporter, on se couche sur les perches au dessus desquelles sont des escorces estendues contre la pluye,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites')
(114, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Customs', 'bark string used in enemy prisoner torture', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:76')
(115, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Technology', 'bark used to cover a lodge', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:47')
(116, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Customs', 'used to build a fire during a healing ceremony. In the traditional story Medicine Men, Gabriel Godfroy (probably) relayed to Dunn that medicine men brought patients into their house, made a fire using tree-bark, stripped the patient down to their breech cloth and sat them down in a stool, danced around the fire and threw fire on the patients head but neer burned them. In this way patients were cured of seizure and other ailments', 'Dunn 1909', '1909', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn 1909')
(117, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Material', 'There are 4 Miami items made in part or whole of bark, including a maple sugar basket, sap tub, and model canoes and paddles, all housed at the National Museum of the American Indian, Washington D.C.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'see attachment: NMAI items')
(118, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Material', 'there is a piece of bark, of Miami origin, coated with vermillion, housed at the Glen Black Laboratory in Indiana', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'NAGPRA Inventory')
(119, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Technology', 'barks of trees used to make dyes for tattooing. \"The colours made use of on these occasions [adorning a victim who is about to be sacrificed to the god of war, or painting dead persons] are the same employed in dyeing their skins, and are drawn from certain earths and from the barks of trees\"', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:119, from Kellogg 1923:110')
(120, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Technology', 'powdered bark from a certain tree, fat, and sometimes vermillion are used to preserve their hair. The hair is also sometimes wrapped in an eel or snakeskin, and braided, hanging down to their middle', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:120, from Kellogg 1923:110-111')
(121, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Technology', 'Corn storage is done by means of bark-lined holes in the ground, especially when they have to leave their village or to hide it from enemies, or by drying and hanging bunches of ears, or threshing. \"Their corn and other fruits are preserved in repositories which they dig in the ground, and which are lined with large pieces of bark. Some of them leave maize in the ear, which is tufted like our onions, and hang them on long poles over the entry of their cabbins [sic]. Others thresh it out and lay it up in large baskets of bark, bored on all sides to hinder it from heating\"', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:122, from Kellogg 1923:112-113')
(122, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Material', 'women make items from bark', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:125, from Kellogg 1923:116')
(123, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Technology', 'bark used to build cabins. \" . . .built of bark, supported by a few posts, and sometimes coarsely plastered on the outside with clay . . . These cabbins are from fifteen to twenty foot broad, and sometimes a hundred in length. In this case they have several fires, each fire serving for a space of thirty feet. . . . The doors are only so many pieces of bark, suspended from the top like the ports of a ship\"', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:127, from Kellogg 1923:118')
(124, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Technology', 'pigeon trap made from a wooden frame with bark nets', 'Rafert 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:74-75; 2ndy source, either heard or read by Lamoine, original source unknown')
(125, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Technology', 'bark used to draw map on, using charcoal', 'Voegelin 1934-1985', '1934-1985', '', '', 0, 0, 'Voegelin 1934-1985:Box 3')
(126, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Use - Material', 'canoes made from bark. \"Kapia married at Fort Wayne a Wea woman; on the Wabash River on a bark canoe to Wea Plains these went . . .\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:manuscript 1556')
(127, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Related Info', 'Peoria observation of Nez Perces when they were held in Miami--\"In the spring, when the bark would slip easily, they would select their tree and cut it and then carefully remove the bark and sew the ends together. This was waterproofed and across the center to hold the sides apart they would put a hole to make it as wide as they wanted.\"', 'Burns 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 2, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938')
(128, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Related Info', 'During hunting, women collect poles and bark and makes a lodge as soon the man has prepared a place for the kettle (two poles to support a cross-piece of wood) and gone off to hunt', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 2, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:47')
(129, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Related Info', 'Algonquians use bark to fill in the wound made from an awl, during ear-piercing which is part of a ritual for five or six month old children. \"After he [the juggler] has ended his pouch a flat bodkin made a bone, and a stout awl, and with the former pierces both ears of the child, and with the awl its nose. He fills the wounds in the ears with little rolls of bark, and in the nose he places the end of a small quill, and leaves it there until the wound is healed by a certain ointment with which he dresses it. When it has healed, he places in the aperture some down of the swan or the wild goose\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:77')
(130, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 'Related Info', 'Upon the death of a man\'s brother Algonquians, neighbors to the surviving brother offer the deceased two gifts in order to remove the tears of his relatives, a mat to lie on and a piece of bark to shelter the corpse from the weather. \"In the speech which they [neighbors] accompany this gift they declare that it is made in order to wipe away the tears of his relatives, and that the mat which they give him is for him to lie on, or [that they give--Blair\'s note] a piece of bark to shelter his corpse from the injurious effects of the weather\"', 'Blair 1911', '1911', '', '', 0, 2, '1680-1718, from Blair 1911:80')
(131, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODgzOjI=', 'Habitat', 'Dry grass: occurs in open areas, meadows, prairies, etc. throughout eastern and western Miami lands', '', '', '', '', 0, 1, 'author\'s note')
(132, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODgzOjI=', 'Habitat', 'Wet grass occurs in wetlands, ponds and slow moving streams', '', '', '', '', 0, 1, 'author\'s note')
(133, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODgzOjI=', 'Use - Technology', 'dry, very fine grass was crushed and used as kindling to catch sparks from fire started with wooden stick and board', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:317-318, \"ils mettent ce morceau de bois sur du bois poury, ou sur de l\'herbe bien seche et bien fine, apres qu\'ils ont eu le soin de la bien ecraser dans leurs mains,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(134, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODgzOjI=', 'Use - Unknown', 'word for dry grass', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(135, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODgzOjI=', 'Use - Material', 'tall grasses used to cover sheds made for drying corn and other foods. \"I think she said when they first come from Indiana there was a tall grass [e.g. tall prairie grasses, like Big bluestem (Andropogon gerardii), Indian grass (Sorghastrum nutans), Switch grass (Panicum virgatum), and Canada wild rye (Elymus canadensis)] that they covered their dry sheds with . . . To dry their corn or somethin\' like that. They tied it down with poles. Now that\'s amazing to me how that would turn [repel] water\"', 'Carver 1968', '1968', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Rose Carver by J.W. Tyner, Miami, OK, 9/9/1968, in MTO Archives')
(136, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODgzOjI=', 'Use - Unknown', '\"mitakatwa, grass, hay, wheat and other cereals, straw of all kinds, is a collective noun\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1264')
(137, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1NzQ5Mjoy', 'Use - Material', 'game with bean-seeds and straws. \"At night most of the men, seated like dogs on mats of round reeds, play with straws. For markers they use the little beans which I have mentioned, which grow on the thorny trees. The game is usually of 200 straws of the length of a foot. The one who can best deceive is the best player, so they are always on the lookout against being deceived. They mark with their beans one or two, according to the wish of the one whose turn it is to mark, then three, and so in regard to the other players up to six, which is the game. One of them takes the straws in both hands and forces his thumb into the middle. The other, if he so desires, does the same thing, and afterwards counts the straws by sixes, if he happens to have one left, and one bean is marked the first, he has the head, if the other gets two which are marked next, it is what they call the neck which comes after the head, so he loses, if he gets one like the other, they begin over again. They have perhaps five or six hundred of these beans, some of which they stake on each play, and when one player has them all before him, they gain what they have staked. They are addicted to this game in a degree that cannot be exceeded [more on their actions regarding the game]', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:351-352 , Deliette 1721, \"et la nuit comme des Chiens la plus part assis sur des nattes de joncs ronds jouent avec des pailles, pour leurs marques ils se servent de ces petites fevves don\'t je viens de parler que ces arbres charges d\'epines raportent, le jeu est ordinairement de 200. pailles de la Longueur d\'un pied, celuy quy scait mieux tromper est le plus habile joueur, ainsi i\" sont toujours sur le qui vive a prendre garde si ils ne ce trompent ils marquent avec leurs graines, un ou deux selon la volonte de celuy a qui s\'est a marquer ensuite trois ainsy des autres jusq\'au nombre de six qui est le jeu un prend les pailles dans ses deux mains et foure le poulce dans le milieu, si c\'est sa volonte L\'autre fait le meme chose et apres compte par six les pailles, si il arrive qu\'il aye un de Reste et qu\'une fevve soit marquee la premiere il a la teste, si l\'autre amenne deux qui seront marquees ensuitte, c\'est ce ce qu\'ils appellent le col qui est apres la teste ainsy ils perd, si il amenne un comme l\'autre ils recommancent, ils ont peut estre 5. ou 600. de ces fevves don\'t ils mettent une partie a chaque coup, et quand un les a toutes devant Luy ils gagnet ce qu\'ils ont mis au jeu, Ils y sont adonnes il ne se peut d\'avantage,\"translation from French to English by Pease')
(138, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1NzQ5Mjoy', 'Use - Customs', 'killing prisoners of war. \"When he [prisoner of war] is condemned to die, it is always by fire. I have never seen any other kind of torment used by this nation. They plant a little tree in the earth, which they make him clasp; they tie his two wrists, and with torches of straw of firebrands they burn him, sometimes for six hours.\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:385, Deliette 1721; \"Quand il est condamne a la mort c\'est toujours par le feu, Je n\'ay jamais vu d\'autres genres de suplices chez cette nation. On plante un petit Arbre dans la terre qu\'on luy fait embrasser, on luy lie les deux poignets Et avec des Torches de pailles out tisons ou le Brule qulquefois pendant six heurs,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(139, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1NzQ5Mjoy', 'Use - Material', 'game of straws played. \"On this day the Poutewatamies came to play at the game of straws, against the Miamis; the game was played in the cabbin of the chief, and in a sort of square over against it. These straws are small rushes of the thickness of a stalk of wheat and two fingers in length. They take up a parcel of these in their hand, which generally consists of two hundred and one, and alwas of an unequal number. After they have well stirred them, and making a thousand contortions of body and invoking the genii, they divide them, with a kind of awl or sharp bone into parcels of ten: each takes one at a venture, and he to whom the parcel with eleven in it falls gains a certain number of points according to the agreement: sixty or four score make a party. There are other ways of playing this game, and they would have explained them to me, but I could understand nothing of the matter, except that the number nine gained the whole party. They also told me, that there was as much of art as chance in this game, and that the Indians are so great cheats at it, as well as at all others; that they are so eager at it, as to spend whole days and nights at it; and that sometimes they do not give over playing till they have stript themselves naked and have nothing more to lose\"', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:102-103, from Kellogg 1923:95-96')
(140, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1NzQ5Mjoy', 'Use - Material', 'straw spread on prisoner in order to facilitate burning. \". . .it is true, an old Illinois woman, whose son had been formerly killed by the Outagamies, did him all the mischief that fury inspired by revenge could invent; at last, however, taking pity on his cries, they covered him with straw, to which they set fire, and as he was still found to breath after this was consumed, he was pierced by arrows by the children . . . he is unworthy, they say, to die by the hands of men\"', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1683-1761:207, from Kellogg 1923:192')
(141, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1NzQ5Mjoy', 'Related Info', 'The Algonquian game of straws utilizes stems, or straws, from a special plant with stems of thickness smaller than the cordage for a salmon-net. \"They take for this sport a certain number of straws, or of the stems of a special plant, which is not so thick as the cord for a salmon-net, and with these they make little sticks all alike in length and thickness, the length is about eleven inches, and the number is uneven\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:96')
(142, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Use - Customs', 'war preparations. \"They also mark places for joining each other in case they are obliged to go by several different routes, and in such cases those who arrive first take a little of what they have left, if they need it, and leave their marks, which they never mistake. They paint a portrait of themselves for this purpose on the nearest tree. Although several of them have heads of hair that look just alike, the mark of their name identifies them.\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:378, Deliette 1721, \"ils marquent aussy des Lieux pour se rejoindre s\'ils sont obligez de faire plusrs. Routes, et en ce cas ceux qui arrivent Les premiers, prennent un peu de ce qu\'ils ont laissez s\'ils en ont besoin et Laissent leurs marques, en quoy ils ne se trompent Jamais ils se depeignent pour cela a l\'arbe Le plus proche, quoy que plusieurs ayent la Chevelure faite de meme, la marque de Leur nom les font connoistre,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(143, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Use - Customs', 'killing prisoners of war. \"When he [prisoner of war] is condemned to die, it is always by fire. I have never seen any other kind of torment used by this nation. They plant a little tree in the earth, which they make him clasp, they tie his two wrists, and with torches of straw of firebrands they burn him, sometimes for six hours.\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:385, Deliette 1721, \"Quand il est condamne a la mort c\'est toujours par le feu, Je n\'ay jamais vu d\'autres genres de suplices chez cette nation. On plante un petit Arbre dans la terre qu\'on luy fait embrasser, on luy lie les deux poignets Et avec des Torches de pailles out tisons ou le Brule qulquefois pendant six heurs,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(144, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Use - Technology', '\"I paint him, make his portrait on a tree, or on a war-club\"', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca.1700:253.10, translation from French to English by Masthay/Suter')
(145, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Use - Customs', 'identifying mark drawn on tree during warring/burning prisoner of war on a tree. Gabriel Godfroy relayed the story of Kaapia, in Miami, to Dunn, which included the description of some Miami men on their way to get revenge for an act of war, following a trail in pursuit of a Kickapoo enemy named Buck . \". . . after a while we saw a buck drawn on a tree. My companions said: \'Its useless. Buck is a real Kickapoo warrior. We\'ll never catch him.\' . . . \'We\'ll keep following him.\' They caught up with him and burned him while tied to a tree\"', 'Dunn 1909', '1909', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn 1909')
(146, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Use - Customs', 'tree branches used to come out of water in creation story. \"They came from the \'Coming out Place\'. The first ones came from out of the water. \"Grab ahold of tree-limbs\" they told each other\"', 'Dunn 1909', '1909', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn 1909, from Gabriel Godfroy, in Miami')
(147, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Use - Technology', 'small tree cut off and hatchet head placed into slit. When tree had grown around hatchet head sufficiently, the tree was cut and a hatchet with firmly held hatchet head was ready for use', 'Charlevoix 1681-1761', '1681-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:126, from Kellogg 1923:117')
(148, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Use - Technology', 'fortifications around villages made with interwoven tree branches. \"The piles of which they [palidade fortifications] are composed, are interwoven with branches of trees, without any void space between\"', 'Charlevoix 1681-1761', '1681-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:128, from Kellogg 1923:118')
(149, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Use - Technology', 'canoes made from single tree trunks. \"A Pirogue . . . This is a long sort of boat made of the trunk of a single tree. Canoes of bark are seldom made use of in these parts\"', 'Charlevoix 1681-1761', '1681-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1683-1761:202, from Kellogg 1923:187')
(150, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Use - Customs', 'the dead are wrapped in skins and hung from the tops of trees. \"Their custom is not to bury the dead, but to wrap them in skins, and to attach them by the head and feet to the tops of trees\"', 'Shea 1903', '1903', '', '', 0, 0, 'Shea 1903:155, footnote to Membre\'s narrative, quoting F. Rale, also an explorer, from Kip\'s Jesuit Relations, p. 38')
(151, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Use - Customs', 'Illinois hung their deceased, wrapped in skins, in the tops of trees. \"The Illinois did not inter their dead. The corpse, carefully wrapped in skins was attached by the head and feet to the upper part of trees\"', 'Talihan 1864', '1864', '', '', 0, 0, 'Tailhan 1864, footnote in Blair 1911:83')
(152, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 'Related Info', 'Algonquians believe that the soul of the deceased, while travelling in a beautiful country on its way to the country of the dead, crosses a fast river which can only be crossed by one slender tree-trunk as a bridge. \"They believe, furthermore, that as soon as the soul has left the body it enters this charming country, and that, after having traveled many days, it encounters on its route a very rapid river, over which there is only a slender tree-trunk by way of bridge, and that in passing over this it bends so much that the soul is in danger of being swept away by the flood waters. They assert that if unfortunately this mishap occurs, the soul will be drowned, but that all these perils are escaped when once the souls have reached the country of the dead\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:89-90')
(153, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3NjE5OjI=', 'Description', '\"The bark is white and the plant grows about two feet high\"', 'Burns 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938')
(154, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3NjE5OjI=', 'Habitat', '\"This grew here [Miami, OK]\"', 'Burns 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938')
(155, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3NjE5OjI=', 'Use - Material', '\"The sinew weed was used to make thread. This grew here and peeling off the bark of the body of the weed could be separated into very fine threads which are strong and durable\"', 'Burns 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938')
(156, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MTcwOjI=', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in wet, moist areas throughout eastern and western Miami lands', '', '', '', '', 0, 1, 'author\'s note')
(157, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MTcwOjI=', 'Use - Technology', 'used in orienteering when traveling cross-country, along with stream courses and size, and the sun. \"Their course in an unknown country is regulated by the moss upon the trees, by the general course of the streams and their size and by the sun\"', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:58')
(158, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MTcwOjI=', 'Use - Technology', 'mukoapineek, are very large roots of the \"pond lily\", and require much preparation. A hole is dug in the ground in which rocks are placed and heated with a fire on top of them. When the fire is done, dry moss is placed over the heated stones and the roots thrown in and covered with grass or moss, bark, water added and then earth covering the top. It is left for five days and then the roots are removed, cut into small pieces, dried on a small scaffold and used later. They are good for a year this way. When used, they are added to a batch of soup before the meat is done cooking.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:64')
(159, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MTcwOjI=', 'Use - Unknown', '', 'Anonymous 1837', '1837', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer')
(160, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MTcwOjI=', 'Use - Unknown', '\"anza\'nzi, moss\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:3314')
(161, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MTcwOjI=', 'Use - Unknown', '\"miza\'nza\" \"moss growing on trees\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1284')
(162, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MTcwOjI=', 'Use - Unknown', '\"ququnruke, green moss\"', 'Kerr 1835', '1835', '', '', 0, 0, 'Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer, from Mongosa')
(163, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MTcwOjI=', 'Related Info', 'Gravier listed this Miami-Illinois phrase: \"ansansigamiwi riviere, ou, maret plain de mousse\", meaning river or marsh full of moss', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gravier ca. 1700')
(164, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzoxMjA3ODoy', 'Description', '\"sunflower\"', 'Gatschet ca. 1895', 'ca. 1895', '', '', 0, 0, '')
(165, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzoxMjA3ODoy', 'Habitat', '\"Grows wild and in profusion in Indian Territory\"', 'Gatschet ca. 1895', 'ca. 1895', '', '', 0, 1, '')
(166, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzoxMjA3ODoy', 'Ecological Info', 'There are a number of sunflowers native to the Indian territory prairies, including the Ashy Sunflower, the Maximillian Sunflower and others. \'Sitakaana\' could be any one of these that were common in the past (Olds 2004, Email communication between Daryl Baldwin, Dustin Olds, and Mike Gonella, 7/15/04);', 'Olds 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 1, '')
(167, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzoxMjA3ODoy', 'Related Info', 'This sunflower was mentioned by Gatschet without mention of its cultural significance. However, the animate \"a\" ending on this term indicates cultural importance during older, including precontact, times. The beginning of the word \"sit-\" is extremely rare in central Algonquian language and no other cognates in other languages have been found (Baldwin 2004, Email communication between Daryl Baldwin, Dustin Olds, and Mike Gonella, 7/15/04);', 'Baldwin 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 2, '')
(168, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzozMjE3MToy', 'Use - Technology', 'yellow dye made from flower heads. \"To dye yellow they take an herb that they call Oncaccou from the name of the color that it gives, it resembles dandelions. They take the heads of this plant which are like a big button, they dry them in the sun, then they crush and boil them without any other ingredient. The dyeing is very beautiful. They go to seek this plant far from the Mississipi. It is in abundance in the river of the Illinois\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:163B, \"Pour teindre en jaune on le fait d\'une herbe qu\'on appelle Oncaccou du nom de la Couleur qu\'elle donne elle reseemble a des pissanlis, On prend les Testes de cette herbe qui sont comme un gros bouton, on les fait secher qu soleil, puis on les pile et fait bouiller sans autre ingredien, la Teinture est fort belle, On va chercher cette herbe loin de Mississipi, il y en a abondament dans La Riviere de Illinois\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(169, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzoxNjUwNjoy', 'Use - Technology', 'root used for red dye. \"To dye red, there is on the prairie of the Tamarcoua [Tamarora] a plant that they name red Micousiouaki, they take the root, they dry it, then then pulverize it in the mortar and then boil it with three times as many sumac berries, the red is very beautiful\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:163B, \"Pour teintre en Rouge, il y a a dans la prairie des Tamarcoua une herbe qu\'on nomme Micousiouaki Rouge, on prend la racine on la fait secher, puis on la pulverise dans le mortier et ensuite en la fais bouiller avec 3 fois autant de graine de Vinaigrier, le Rouge est fort beau\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(170, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo2MTkxOjI=', 'Use - Medicinal', 'bark boiled and used on all types of wounds, to stop bloody flux and cure a cancer. \"The bark of lead wood boiled for all sorts of wounds, I have seen a cancer cured, it sserves to stop the bloody flux, we must carry some of this wood to France\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:164A, \"De l\'ecois de Bois de plomb bouilly pour toutes sortes de playes, j\'avay veu gueris un Cancer, il sert pour arreter le flux de sang, il faut emporter de ce bois en France\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(171, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo4MzM5ODoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'used to treat cuts. \"The herb of a thousand leaves for all sorts of cuts\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:164B, \"De l\'herbe a mille feuilles pour toutes sorts de Coupures\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004; the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(172, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MDY4ODoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'leaves boiled and used to treat sore eyes. \"The leaves of Listre boiled for soreness of the eyes\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:164B, \"De la feuilles de Listre bouillee pour les douleurs des yeux\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(173, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo4MDgzNToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'root boiled and used to draw out objects in wounds. \"For wounds and for to draw out that which is in the wound musket ballor other thing, it is necessary toboil the root of a certain reed which bears distaffs. I have seen the test of this remedy\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:164B, \"Pour les playes et pour attirer ce qui on dans la playe boule de fusile ou autre chose, il faut faire bouiller de la racine d\'un certain Rozeau qui porte des quenouilles j\'ay veu leexperience de ce remede\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(174, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo4MDgzNToy', 'Use - Material', 'Shopekenauminkee is a game played with a hundred pieces of small reed or cane about a foot in length. The players take turns taking the bunch of reeds between their hands and letting them drop end-wise upon the bark board where they play, trying to drop them so that five pieces, corresponding to the head and limbs, fall together.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:64')
(175, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo4MDgzNToy', 'Use - Technology', 'they used a bundle of round reeds for kindling to start a fire, with two bits of wood for striking the flame, for cooking their meat', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:316-317, \"un d\'eux fut a 3. ou 4. arpents dans un fond ou le printemps ce n\'est qu\'une maniere de marais, et apporterent une botte de Roseaux ronds qui sont gros comme les doigts, tirerent de leur Crquois deux morceaux de Bois, qui leur sert de batte feu, Et en moins d\'un demy misere en eurent fait, ils allumerent une partie de leurs Roseaux, sur quoy ils mirent leur vande, qu\'ils tournoient de temps en temps avec leur arcs,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(176, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo4MDgzNToy', 'Use - Technology', 'little reeds probably used in making some type of arrow shaft. \"atchihar8\"', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca.1700, translated by Masthay 2003:80, rel info 1')
(177, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo4MDgzNToy', 'Related Info', 'The \'ar8\' ending (-arwa, arwi, alwi) is usually seen with the names of types of arrows (e.g. ahtawaanhsalwi, \'pointed wooden arrow\') and also appears on some plant names that probably all have to do with arrow production (e.g. Gatschet\'s \'napahalwi\', ash tree, and Illinois/Peoria \'iihkalwi\', dogwood). Therefore, the word \'atchihar8\' is a plural noun for some type of reed having to do with arrow production', 'McCafferty 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 2, 'McCafferty\'s explanation in an email communication between Costa and McCafferty, March 20, 2003, regarding Masthay\'s listing of this word')
(178, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzozNTIyOjI=', 'Use - Medicinal', 'root of small fern boiled and resulting liquid used to treat bloody flux. \"The best and the most prompt remedy that I have seen for the bloody flux is the root of the fern which bears very small seeds, it is necessary to boil it over a small fire or to steep it until the water is red, and when it has diminished about a third, make the patient take a quarter of a litre on an empty stomach until a complete cure. One can take it in the evening to be cured sooner, three, four, or fives times at least will do the trick\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:164B-165A, \"Le meilleur est le plus prompt Remede qui j\'ay veu pour le flux de sang, c\'est de la Racine de feugere qui porte de la graine, et de la plus petite, il fait ca faire bouiller a petit feu ou infuser jusqu\'a ce que l\'Eau soit rouge, et qu\'elle ay diminue environ de tierst, en faire prendre au malade un demy septier a jeun jusqu\'a parfaite guerison, on en peu prendre le fois pour etre plus on guery 3.4. ou cinq fois au plus en seront l\'affaire\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(179, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo4Nzc1NToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'bark chewed or crushed to treat wounds. \"The bark of samelier or Ebeaupain chewed ro crushed for wounds\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:165A, \"De l\'ecois de samelier ou Ebeaupain machee ou pilee pour les Playes\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(180, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MjgwMDoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'used to treat veneral diseases. \"The white creeper, for veneral diseases\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:165A, \"De la Lianne Blanche pour les maux veneriens\" translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(181, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo5NTUyNToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'bark of ash used to treat sprains. \"For accidents or sparins, the bark of the ash hybrid, chewed and put on the inury\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:165A, \"Pour les maux d\'avanture ou fouleure, de l\'ecoise de fresne Mestis, machee en mettre sur le mal\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(182, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MDg3MToy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"species of a berry, its name unknown to my informant\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:3646-3647')
(183, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MDg3MToy', 'Use - Food', '\"lachaminic peas\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895')
(184, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MDg3MToy', 'Use - Food', '\"aleciminiiki peas\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:151em')
(185, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MDg3MToy', 'Related Info', 'Dunn lists the word [latci]miniki as the plural form of the word latcimina, meaning pea. This corresponds closely to Gatschet\'s term alatchimini for a species of berry, unknown to his informant', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 2, 'Dunn ca. 1900:3647dw; Gatschet ca. 1895')
(186, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MDg3MToy', 'Related Info', 'Possibly an older word for a wild pea-like plant, although its contemporary meaning is the cultivated pea', '', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s note')
(187, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MzY2Njoy', 'Use - Material', '\"kipakaxkatwa, green grass\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1205')
(188, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MzY2Njoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"ikipakaxki mitakatwi, green grass, weeds, stalks. The plural kipakaxkatwa refers to different species of grass and weeds\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1264, 1325')
(189, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MzY2Njoy', 'Related Info', 'lists the general Miami-Ilinois term for green grass as \"kipakaxkatwi\", indicating green grass, weeds and stalks, where the plural form \"kipakaxkatwa\" refers to different species of grass and weeds. He also lists a phrase \"kipakaxkatw malimawiki, or milamayuwi\" translated as \'the grasses are full of dew\'\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:77, p.1205')
(190, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MzY2Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Dunn lists the word Miami-Illinois term for green grass as \"ihkipakahkatwi\", translated as solely, green grass;', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 2, 'Dunn (ca. 1900)')
(191, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo5NTQ4NToy', 'Habitat', 'Moist or dry upland woods in eastern and western Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(192, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo5NTQ4NToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'used to cure snakebites. According to Kenton 1925, this species or Polygala senega could possibly be the one referred to by Marquette, in his 1674 letter in the Jesuit Relations', 'Marquette 1674', '1674', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:340 footnote')
(193, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoxNTEzMDoy', 'Description', 'A small bush, similar to the huckleberry, which grows on the prairies and has a short, thick, red root', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(194, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoxNTEzMDoy', 'Habitat', 'Ceanothus americanus, sometimes called New Jersey tea, or redroot, or C. herbaceus, called Prairie redroot were probably both indicated by \'neehpikiccikaahkwi\', both growing in prairies through Indiana and Oklahoma', '', '', '', '', 0, 1, 'Author\'s note')
(195, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoxNTEzMDoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'thick red root made into tea for curing \"any disease\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Finley, in Dunn ca. 1900')
(196, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoxNTEzMDoy', 'Use - Customs', 'A traditional story recounts some Peorias that wanted to scare off a white family looking for a house to lease. \"Before the time for their [the white family] return he gathered up turkey feathers and made a large head-dress, smeared his face with red paint from redroot and some yellow clay, dressed himself in some old beaded clothing and, armed with a huge tomahawk, waited for them by the side of the road, concealed in some bushes. When they were even with him he sprang to the road with a wild yell, brandishing his tomahawk. The family left as fast as their horses would travel and never returned and Uncle John never tired of laughing over his \"Wild Indian Stunt.\"', 'Burns 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938, this reference may not refer to the same \"redroot\" as entry #1')
(197, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoxNTEzMDoy', 'Related Info', 'A tea was made from the leaves during the American Revolution. No caffeine is found in the leaves, but the root was once used as an expectorant and astringent, and the root bark has been found to have many blood-clotting properties.', 'Steyermark 1963', '1963', '', '', 0, 2, 'Steyermark 1963')
(198, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo5OTAzNToy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in moist woods and bogs in eastern Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist', '', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist')
(199, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo5OTAzNToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'used as an antidote to snakebite venom. \"use wahe\'ahchippykick either by holding a piece of the root in the mouth or by making a tea and holding the tea in the mouth\"', 'Bussard 1960', '1960', '', '', 0, 0, 'Bussard ca. 1960, from Bundy')
(200, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo5OTAzNToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'medicinal plant used as an antidote to snakebite venom. \"asanitcipki, colic root or devils bit, medicinal plant said to kill poison\", also \"wawiatcipki\", or waawiyaaciipihki\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:1268-9')
(201, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo5OTAzNToy', 'Related Info', 'These entries may also refer to \'eehseniciipihki\', or Aletris farinosa', '', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s note')
(202, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo3NTA2OToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'root used to cure rattlesnake bite. \"Rattlesnakes abound among them, not a summer passes but some one is bitten, this troubles them but little since they have an admirable root, which, as soon as it is applied to the wound, softens the swelling so that by the next day one is cured. This root is found in the prairies and is shaped like an onion. The stem grows two feet high, the leaves are narrow and somewhat resemble those of the sumac. It forms large buds in which the seed is lodged. I have made a point of hunting for it in this country, but have never been able to find any. I have been told that they had still another kind, but I have not become acquainted with it.\"', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, Pease 1934:372, \"Il y a une grande quantite de serpens a sonnette chez eux, il ne se passe point d\'annee qu\'il n\'y aye quelqu\'un de pique de quoy ils s\'embarassent tres peu parce qu\'ils ont d\'une Racine admirable, sitot qu\'on en a mis sur la playe elle fait amolir L\'enflure et le Lendemain on est guery, cette Racine se trouve dans Les prairies et est faitte comme un oignon, Le tige vient de deux pieds de deux pieds de haut, La feuille fort etroitte qui aproche celle des Vinaigriers, Il se forme de gros Boutons dans quoy est la raine, je me suis attachez a en chercher dans ce pays mais je n\'en ay jamais pu trouver, on ma dit qu\'il y en avoit encore d\'une autre sorte, mais je ne la connois point,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(203, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo3NTA2OToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'root used as antidote to snake bites. The root of this plant must first be chewed and then placed on the snake bite. \"I also took time to look for a medicinal plant which a savage, who knows its secret, showed to Father Alloues with many Ceremonies. Its root is employed to Counteract snake-bites, God having been pleased to give this antidote Against a poison which is very common in these countries. It is very pungent, and tastes like powder when crushed with the teeth, it must be masticated and place upon the bite inflicted by the snake. The reptile has so great a horror of it that it even flees from a person who has rubbed himself with it. The plant bears serveral stalks, a foot high, with rather long leaves, and a white flower, which greatly resembles The wallflower\"', 'Marquette 1673', '1673', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1673, from Thwaites 1966:101, \"Je pris aussi le temps de reconnoistre un simple qu\'un sauvage qui en scait le secret a enseigne au P. Alloues auec beaucoup de Ceremonies, Sa racine sert Contre la morsure des serpent, Dieu ayant voulu donner ce remede Contre un venin qui est tres frequent en ces pays: Elles est fort chaude et elle a un goust de poudrre quand on l\'escrase sou sous la dent, il faut la mascher et la mettre sur la piquure du serpent, qui en a une si grande horreur, qu\'il s\'enfuit mesme de Celuy qui s\'en est frotte, elle produit plusieures tiges hautes d\'un pied, dont la feuille est un peu longue et la fleur blanche et beaucoup semblable a La giroflee,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites')
(204, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo3NTA2OToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'antidote to snake bites. \" . . .I had the curiosity to taste the mineral water of a river near it [a Miami/Maskouten/Kickapoo village], and found a simple [plant] of a wonderful virtue against the venom of the serpents. A savage who knew it, had shown it to Father Allouez, who had often occasion to try its virtues, God having been pleased to provide that country with that wonderful antidote against the serpents, who are very dangerous in those parts. The root of the simple is very hot, and tastes like gunpowder; they chew it, and apply it to the part of the body stung by the serpents; and this without any other mystery cures the wound; and the serpents have such an antipathy aginst the herb, that they run away from any man who has rubb\'d his body with the same. It produces several stalks about a foot high; the leaves are somewhat long; the flower is white, and the whole looks like our Gilliflowers. I took one into our canow, the better to examine it\"', 'Joliet 1673', '1673', '', '', 0, 0, 'Joliet 1673:199, from Thwaites 1903:640. This entry is very similar to entry #4--Joliet and Marquette traveled together through the Illinois county. It is possible that when compiling their separate memoirs, they looked at each others notes for additional information. This remedy was relayed to Father Allouez during his time with the Ottawas at Green Bay area, which implies that this remedy was Miami also')
(205, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo3NTA2OToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'antidote to snakebite. Hennepin does not specify the plant used, but this and Devil\'s bit are the other two plants mentioned by other ethnographers related to treating snake bites. \"As there are some stony Places in this Country, where there is a great quantity of Serpents, very troublesome to the Illinois, they know several Herbs which are a quiker and surer Remedy against their Venom, than our Treacle or Orvietan. They rub themselves with these Herbs, after which they play with those dangerous Serpents, without receiving any hurt. They take the young ones and put them sometimes into their Mouth\"', 'Hennepin 1698', '1698', '', '', 0, 0, 'Hennepin 1698, from Thwaites 1903:168')
(206, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo3NTA2OToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'snakebite antidote. \"As there are in their country many serpents, these Indians know herbs much superior to our orvietan and theriaque, for after rubbing themselves with them, they can without fear play with the most venomous insects, and even put them some distance down their throat\"', 'Membre 1680-1681', '1680-1681', '', '', 0, 0, 'Membre 1680-1681 regarding La Salle, from Shea 1903:156')
(207, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo2MzgyNToy', 'Description', 'A mushroom with leathery polypores, with colors in concentric circles, i.e. man\'s face, ilanongwia', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900: Indiana State Library L47, Note #35')
(208, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo2MzgyNToy', 'Description', 'Fomitopsis spp. is a genus of fungi that grow on trees and have a flat bottom and often semi-conical top portion that could resemble a man\'s nose, and together with the tree could resemble a man\'s face. Dr. Nicholas Money (Miami University) says this is a good guess for this Miami plant, since it is very common in the Midwest and the description fits', 'Money 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'author\'s conversation with Dr. Money, 2005')
(209, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo2MzgyNToy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"ilanongwia, fungus with markings, growing laterally on logs or trees (i-la:no\'ngia) literally mans face\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:Indiana State Library L47, Note #35')
(210, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo1NjE1Njoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'plant used to cure inflammation caused by another plant [poison ivy, poison sumac]. \"plant which cures this inflammation/swelling[from having touched some bad plant]. Also marking the swelling that comes from scratching\"', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca.1700:292.90, \"herbe qui guerit cette enflure. Item marque l\'enflure qui vient pour gratter,\" translation from French to English by Masthay, year needed')
(211, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoxNzk2OjI=', 'Use - Medicinal', 'roots boiled for all types of wounds. \"The root of onis [wild marjoram?] [Anonymous\' brackets] boiled for all sorts of wounds\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:164A,\"De la Racine d\'Onis [onitide?] bouilly pour toutes sortes de playes\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
