(298, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo4Nzg4OToy', 'Use - Food', 'modern traditional food/crop. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895')
(299, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo1Mzk4MDoy', 'Description', 'May refer to A. sativum, cultivated garlic, or A. vineale or A. canadense, wild garlic', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 0, 'Small 190, Coulter 1899, Steyermark 1963, Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(300, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo1Mzk4MDoy', 'Habitat', 'A. sativum L. is a cultivated species native of western Asia, occuring in cultivated areas and rarely as an escape throughout eastern and western Miami lands. A. vineale L. (field garlic or scallions) is a native of Europe and found in lawns and fields as a weed throughout eastern (Gleason and Cronquist) and western Miami lands (Steyermark 1963?). A. canadense L. (bulb ovoid-conic?) is a native garlic ocurring in open woods and prairies throughout eastern and western Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(301, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo1Mzk4MDoy', 'Use - Unknown', 'wild onion', 'Anonymous 1837', '1837', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer')
(302, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo1Mzk4MDoy', 'Use - Food', '\"luqenfefuke, garlic\"', 'Kerr 1835', '1835', '', '', 0, 0, 'Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer, from Mongosa, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909')
(303, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo4NjE3Mzoy', 'Description', '\". . . the root is like a leek, and the plant which grows from it resembles the salsify. This onion, I declare, is so exceedingly acrid that if one tries to swallow it, it would all at once wither the tongue, the throat, and the inside of the mouth; I do not know, however, whether it would have the same injurious effect on the inside of the body . . .\"', 'Dunn 1919', '1919', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn 1919, from Perrot')
(304, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo4NjE3Mzoy', 'Habitat', '\"The tribes of the prairies also find in certain places lands that are fertile, and kept moist by the streams that water them, whereon grow onions of the size of ones thumb\"', 'Dunn 1919', '1919', '', '', 0, 1, 'Dunn 1919, from Perrot')
(305, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo4NjE3Mzoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in various habitats, prairies, open, dry or rich wood', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(306, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo4NjE3Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'corms eaten. \"When the savages lay in a store of these onions, with which the ground is covered, they first build an oven, upon which they place the onions, covering them with a thick layer of grass; and by means of the heat which the fire communicates to them the acrid quality leaves them, nor are they damaged by the flames; and after they have been dried in the sun they become an excellent article of food\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 0, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Dunn 1919')
(307, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo4NjE3Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'corms and leaves eaten .\"The wild onion is still eaten by the Miamis as an early vegetable, but without this formidable preparation. They are washed, cut fine, and fried in grease until they wilt; then a little water is added, with salt, pepper and enough flour to cream. This removes the acrid taste\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
