(532, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MDE4MDoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"tcatcingilakakwa\" Wea word for shell-bark hickory', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn Report ca. 1900:102 & 2676dw')
(533, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MDE4MDoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"tchatchingilakaxkwa pakani, shellbark hickory nut\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1725')
(534, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MDE4MDoy', 'Related Info', 'Bartram (1739-1823) described the Creek\'s processing of shell-barked hickory nuts. \"I have seen above an hundreds of bushels of these nuts belonging to one family. They pound them to pieces, and then cast them into boiling water, which, after passing through fine strainers, preserves the most oily part of the liquid: this they call by a name which signifies hiccory milk, it is as sweet and rich as fresh cream, and is an ingredient in most of their cookery, especially in homony [sic] and corn cakes.\"', 'Van Doren 1928', '1928', '', '', 0, 2, 'Van Doren 1928:57, Bartram')
(535, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MDE4MDoy', 'Related Info', 'Shell-bark hickory has been reported to produce 3 bushels of nuts per tree, yielding approximately 42 pounds of edible nutmeat per tree, per year--seven trees being enough to feed one person for a year', 'Gardner 1997', '1997', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gardner 1997:103')
(536, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MDE4MDoy', 'Related Info', 'Archaeological studies have demonstrated that nuts (preserved as nutshell, which represent walnut, hickory and hazelnut species) were an important wild food resource utilized by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana. Results of these studies indicate that nut use declined over the Late Woodland period (prior to 700 A.D. to 1450 A.D.), probably due to increased cultivation of fall-maturing crops, like corn, and conflicts with gathering nuts during this same time period', 'Bush 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 2, 'Bush 2003')
(537, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MDE4MDoy', 'Related Info', 'Dunn listed the Miami term \"tcatcingilakakwa\" for the shell-bark hickory (Dunn rep. p102), where Hockett listed \"cecingilakya\" [special characters changed to regular alphabet] (Hockett 1938:140) and Thornton listed \"tshatshinggalukeh\"', 'Thornton 1802', '1802', '', '', 0, 2, 'Thornton 1802')
(538, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2Nzc0NDoy', 'Description', 'Smooth-bark hickory: The species indicated by this Miami word was probably the saplings of one or more of the following: Carya ovata, Shagbark hickory, C. glabra, Pignut hickory, or C. laciniosa, Shell-bark hickory. The bark of each of these species is relatively smooth for the first few years of its life, then turning furrowed, or scaley, but not extremely', 'Small 1903', '1903', '', '', 0, 0, 'Small 1903; Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(539, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2Nzc0NDoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in rich, moist soils', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(540, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2Nzc0NDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'wood for long bows was made from the smooth-bark hickory (kwassiani kupa), one split sapling making two long bows and other bows made from buffalo ribs. Bird arrows made with blunt points of hickory wood. The sweat lodge in Peoria was made of hickory branches or other material that bent easily', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900-Peoria')
(541, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2Nzc0NDoy', 'Use - Unknown', 'kwassianikupa, smooth-bark hickory', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895')
(542, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2Nzc0NDoy', 'Related Info', 'Archaeological studies have demonstrated that nuts (preserved as nutshell, which represent walnut, hickory and hazelnut species) were an important wild food resource utilized by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana. Results of these studies indicate that nut use declined over the Late Woodland period (prior to 700 A.D. to 1450 A.D.), probably due to increased cultivation of fall-maturing crops, like corn, and conflicts with gathering nuts during this same time period', 'Bush 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 2, 'Bush 2003')
(543, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2Nzc0NDoy', 'Related Info', 'The term \"kwaciani\'kopa\" was used for hickories, in general', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 2, 'Dunn ca. 1900:102report')
(544, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2Nzc0NDoy', 'Related Info', 'The term \"qefeneqopu\" also refers to the hickory', 'Kerr 1835', '1835', '', '', 0, 2, 'Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer,from Mongosa')
(545, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in rich, moist soils', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(546, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Technology', 'bird arrows with a blunt point made out of dogwood and hickory wood, both which sink in the water', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(547, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Material', 'Shingaukekaunekee is a game played on the ice, with a bow, about fifteen feet long, four inches wide and a half an inch thick, made from hickory or another hard wood. \"it may be said to resemble a sleigh runner rather than a bow, in shape, and one end is thicker & heavier than the other.\" Two people play, and each has a boundary, quite far apart, that the other tries to obtain by throwing the bow. The bow is thrown to move towards the far boundary, each person trying to gain their own boundary behind their opponent. The whole village is involved, and there are objects of value staked upon the game, by the villagers. Sometimes the game starts by one village sending a challenge to another village, by way of a miniature bow, decorated with the items to be staked upon the game. Poles are set up during the game, for hanging these items used for betting.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:63')
(548, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Unknown', 'peesiananikopa means hickory tree, \"pacianikopa, hickory\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(549, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Unknown', 'The term \'kwacianikopa\' was used generically for the hickory tree by the Peoria', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(550, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Technology', 'stems hollowed out using a willow branch, then a whittled down hickory stick placed inside along with a paper wad to make a \'pop-gun\'', 'Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(551, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909')
(552, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Technology', 'hickory bark bundles lit and used as torches for night spear fishing. \"But they also made it of hickory bark and fastened it in bundles and fired that and made torches with that, to walk by at night and spear fish . . . This getting fish at night when the water\'s clear was the best way in the world to get them\"', 'Rafert 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview tih Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:35; 2ndy source, original unknown--he read about this tradition')
(553, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Technology', 'Peoria arrows were made of hickory and dogwood', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Frank Beaver, from Gatschet ca. 1895:2661')
(554, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Technology', 'bark used for making canoes. \"The Miamis did not use birch-bark canoes, which the Algonquians usually called tci-maun, but they sometimes made canoes of hickory or elm bark. The name for these is la-kik-kwi-mis-so-li or bark canoe\"', 'Dunn 1908', '1908', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn 1908:manuscript 1701')
(555, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Material', 'temporary houses made of bent hickory branches and other trees to form a dome. \"nusikani, sweat-lodge or aboriginal sudatory. These temporary structures consisted of bent branches of hickory or other trees, and planted in the ground on both ends. A buffalo or cowhile was thrown over the circular space within, and after excluding the outside air, heated stones were brought inside and steam developed by throwing water\"', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'erf - reference info missing')
(556, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"pakanizhi\", \"pakana tawani\" and \"pakanizhaxkwi\" all mean the \"hickory tree in all its species as enumerated under pakani\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1726')
(557, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"qefeneqopu, hickory\"', 'Anonymous 1837', '1837', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer, 2nd Wea Primer')
(558, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'nuts gathered for eating', 'Tippman 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005')
(559, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Use - Technology', 'wood used to make bow', 'Weisenberger 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Jacob Weisenberger, 2004; speaking of his father\'s plant use')
(560, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Related Info', 'A Peoria observation of Nez Perces when they were held in Miami--\"To make their bows they would bury their hickory poles in the coals until the outside of the poles charred and then they would scrape off the charred portion. This was repeated until the pole became the size wanted and in this way the wood was seasoned at the same time.\"', 'Burns 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 2, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938')
(561, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Related Info', 'Archaeological studies have demonstrated that nuts (preserved as nutshell, which represent walnut, hickory and hazelnut species) were an important wild food resource utilized by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana. Results of these studies indicate that nut use declined over the Late Woodland period (prior to 700 A.D. to 1450 A.D.), probably due to increased cultivation of fall-maturing crops, like corn, and conflicts with gathering nuts during this same time period', 'Bush 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 2, 'Bush 2003')
(562, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Related Info', 'Great Lakes tribes, in general, use sweats to treat many illnesses. To provoke a sweat, hickory wood and pine branches are boiled in a kettle under the person, causing a profuse sweat', 'Charlevoix 1682', '1682', '', '', 0, 2, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:175, from Kellogg 1923:163')
(563, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Related Info', 'Allouez remarked about the Illinois\' use of bow and arrow: \"They ordinarily carry only the warclub, bow, and a quiver full of arrows, which they discharge so adroitly and quickly, that men armed with guns, have hardly time to raise them to the shoulder. They also carry a large buckler made of skins of wild cattle; which is arrow-proof, and covers the whole body\"', 'Allouez 1677', '1677', '', '', 0, 2, 'Allouez 1677, from Shea 1903:78')
(564, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 'Related Info', 'Human-charred hickory shell material recovered from excavations at an early 19th century Miami village site', 'Bush 1996', '1996', '', '', 0, 2, 'Bush 1996:181')
(565, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MjQ2MToy', 'Description', 'Chestnuts eaten by Indians were reportedly \"bigger and finer than those of Lyons,\" ();', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:348-349, Deliette 1721')
(566, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MjQ2MToy', 'Habitat', 'Originally occurred on acid upland soils throughout eastern Miami lands, but now almost eliminated due to blight ();', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(567, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MjQ2MToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'leaves used for coughs, especially whooping coughs', 'Lamb and Shultz 1964', '1964', '', '', 0, 0, 'Lamb and Shultz 1964:38, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy')
(568, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MjQ2MToy', 'Use - Food', 'roasted and eaten. \"There are Indian chestnuts of admirable beauty full of nuts bigger and finer than those of Lyons. There is no one who on seeing them does not believe them to be excellent.\" They were reportedly very bitter, even after cooking on a fire.', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:348-349; \"Il y a des maroniers d\'inde d\'une beaute a admirer remplies de marons plus gros et plus beaux que ceux de lion, il ny a personne en les voyant qui ne croient qu\'ils soient Excellentes . . . j\'en mordis un croyant manger le meilleur maron du monde, mais je fus bien paye de ma Curiosite car je fus plus d\'un quart d\'heure sans pouvoir m\'oster l\'amertume qu\'il m\'avoit laisse a la bouche,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(569, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MjQ2MToy', 'Related Info', 'Human-charred chestnut nutshell and nutmeat material were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River', 'Bush 1996', '1996', '', '', 0, 2, 'Bush 1996:181')
(570, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MjQ2MToy', 'Related Info', 'LeBoullenger has \"mamichimina\" for chestnut, and Thornton has \"mamishiminjeh\", for chestnut tree', 'Costa 2006', '2006', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s note, info from Costa, pers. comm. 2006')
(571, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMzQzMDoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in a moist, rich soils including floodplains throughout eastern and western Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(572, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMzQzMDoy', 'Use - Customs', 'boards lining sides of burial holes. \"pakamakaninji, hackberry\" used to make puncheon of hackberry made pieces for top, bottom, sides and ends of holes', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:2465')
(573, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMzQzMDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'young shoots of hackberry, elm and poplar fed to livestock during hard times', 'Burns 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938')
(574, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMzQzMDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'used for firewood. \"The tree gives good fuel\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1719')
(575, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMzQzMDoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"papaaki\'mini, hackberry berry\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(576, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMzQzMDoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"apakamanganingi\", hackberry', 'Pinet 1696', '1696', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pinet 1696-ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117')
(577, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMzQzMDoy', 'Related Info', 'The Peoria of OK cut up the tender shoots of hackberry, elm and poplar for cattle fodder', 'Burns 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 2, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938')
(578, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMzQzMDoy', 'Related Info', 'The Miami term \"pakamakani\" refers to the berry of the hackberry, \"the dark red berry of the hackberry tree\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1719')
