(580, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo0MzkyOjI=', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in moist woods throughout eastern and western Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(581, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo0MzkyOjI=', 'Use - Unknown', 'redbud or \'judas tree\', with yellow wood', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:3936dw')
(582, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo0MzkyOjI=', 'Use - Unknown', '\"ayunzawikisha\" -- in this name the adjective \"-unzawi\" yellow refers to the yellow graining of the tree, indicated also by Finley', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:456')
(583, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo0MzkyOjI=', 'Use - Food', 'young, tender pods cooked like snow peas. Flowers eaten raw or dried and added to soups', 'Tippman 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005')
(584, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo4MzQ3NToy', 'Habitat', 'Native to tropical America, occurring as a weed in disturbed areas throughout eastern and western Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(585, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo4MzQ3NToy', 'Use - Food', 'young leaves gathered and cooked as greens. \" It was used as a spring tonic for cleansing the body. The young leaves of poke, curly dock and lamb\'s quarter\'s were gathered near my house, mixed together and cooked with vinegar\"', 'Davis 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Judy Davis, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/1/04')
(586, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo4MzQ3NToy', 'Use - Food', 'greens collected and eaten. Seeds collected and made into flour, cut in half with wheat flour', 'Tippman 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005')
(587, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo4MzQ3NToy', 'Use - Food', '\"waapinkopakahki\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn, Peoria fieldnotes ca. 1900')
(588, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo4MzQ3NToy', 'Related Info', 'Volative oil distilled from fresh aboveground portions of the flowering and fruiting plant of Chenopodium ambrosioides var. anthelminticum, in small doses (1cc) has been used to treat round-, tape-, and hook-worms. In general, it increases cardiac rate, promotes secretions of bronchial tubes and kidneys, and has been used to treat hysteria', 'Coulter 1932', '1932', '', '', 0, 2, 'Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.')
(589, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo4MzQ3NToy', 'Related Info', 'McPherson wrote, \"It is believed that prior to introduction of corn prehistoric Indians in Indiana cultivated lamb\'s quarters [Chenopodium sp.] is a green for its seeds. It is high in vitamins A and C and an excellent source of calcium\"', 'McPherson 1977', '1977', '', '', 0, 2, '1977:81, 2ndy source without primary source citation')
(590, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo4MzQ3NToy', 'Related Info', 'Archaeological studies have demonstrated that goosefoot was either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" for consumption of seeds by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana', 'Bush 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 2, 'Bush 2003')
(591, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2NDI0Mzoy', 'Use - Customs', 'flower head pulled out of sepals/receptable and chewed. \"A good chewing toboacco substitute that makes a nice purple spit\"', 'Tippman and Swenda 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman & Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005')
(592, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMTM1Njoy', 'Habitat', 'Also known as C. colocynthis, hence \'coloquinte\', C. vulgaris is a native to Africa cultivated throughout eastern and western Miami lands', 'Hickman 1993', '1993', '', '', 0, 1, 'Hickman 1993')
(593, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMTM1Njoy', 'Use - Food', 'eaten raw', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(594, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMTM1Njoy', 'Use - Food', 'fruits eaten. \"They harvest also a great many watermelons which are admirable. I have seen numbers of them as big as water buckets\"', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:344-345; \"Elles recueillent aussi quantite de melons d\'eau qui sont admirables j\'en ay vu quantite d\'aussi gros qu\'un seau,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(595, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMTM1Njoy', 'Use - Food', 'given to missionaries to eat', 'Kenton 1925', '1925', '', '', 0, 0, 'Kenton 1925:364, The Jesuit Relations')
(596, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMTM1Njoy', 'Use - Unknown', '', 'Anonymous 1837', '1837', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer')
(597, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMTM1Njoy', 'Use - Food', '\"They have abundance of water-melons, citruls, and gourds\"', 'Joliet 1674', '1674', '', '', 0, 0, 'Joliet 1674:186, from Thwaites 1903:622')
(598, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMTM1Njoy', 'Use - Food', 'dried and eaten. \"They greatly esteem their citruls, though they are none of the best. They dry them up, and keep them till the Winter and Spring\"', 'Thwaites 1903', '1903', '', '', 0, 0, 'Thwaites 1903:652, from Marquette 1673:209-210')
(599, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMTM1Njoy', 'Use - Food', 'given to Marquette and Jolliet\'s party to eat. \"We ate no other fruit there than watermelons\"', 'Marquette 1673', '1673', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1673, from Thwaites 1966 (reprint from 1900:59); \"nous n\'y avons pas mange de fruictz que des melons d\'eau,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites')
(600, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMTM1Njoy', 'Use - Food', 'modern traditional crop. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909')
