(765, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Use - Food', 'tubers eaten, called \"Indian potatoes\" and \"the Jerusalem artichoke (Helianthus tuberosa) appears to me to meet his (Perrot\'s) description more nearly than any other plant, and its tubers were eaten by the Indians\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 0, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Dunn 1919')
(766, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Use - Food', '\"As soon as they found out about it, they used the Jerusalem artichoke, but they didn\'t have \'em native here in this country.\"', 'Marks 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:97-98')
(767, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Use - Food', '\"They also store up onions, as big as Jerusalem artichokes, which they find in the prairies, and which I find better than all the other roots. They are sugary and pleasing to the palate. They are cooked like macopines\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:347, Deliette 1721; \"Elles amassent aussi des oignons gros comme des Topiniamboures, qu\'elles trouvent dans les prairies que je trouve meilleures que toutes les autres Racines, ils sont sucre et font plaisir a manger on les fait cuire comme les Macopines,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(768, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Use - Food', 'sunflowers are grown as a crop, probably indicating the jerusalem artichoke', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:121, from Kellogg 1923:112')
(769, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Use - Food/Medicinal', 'oil from the seeds is used for rubbing on the skin. \"The Indians make no other use of the turnsoles, but to extract from them an oil with which they rub themselves: this is more commonly drawn from the seeds than from the root of this plant. This root differs little from what we call in France topinambours or apples of the earth [this plant is probably jerusalem artichoke]\"', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:125, from Kellogg 1923:115')
(770, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Use - Food', 'tubers eaten. \'onzapakataki\", \"indian potatoes\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(771, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Use - Food', 'tubers gathered, cooked and eaten', 'Tippman 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005')
(772, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Horticultural Info', '\"But as soon as they found out about them they cultivated them and used them.\"', 'Marks 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989')
(773, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Horticultural Info', 'Sunflowers, along with watermelons and gourds are first sprouted in a hot-bed and then transplanted into crop fields', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:121, from Kellogg 1923:112')
(774, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Related Info', 'The Shawnee collected this plant for food', 'Clark 1993', '1993', '', '', 0, 2, 'Clark 1993')
(775, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Related Info', 'Many Indian tribes of North America used the tubers of this plant for food. Sometimes, archaeologists are able to locate the sites of old Indian villages by the presence of large stands of Jerusalem artichoke plants. Spanish explorers brought this plant back to Europe where it was cultivated and sold as \'girasol\', the spanish word for sunflower. The English incorrectly tranformed \'girasol\' to Jerusalem, and the \'artichoke\' part of the name comes presumably from the tuber\'s taste', 'McPherson 1977', '1977', '', '', 0, 2, 'McPherson 1977:173-174: 2ndy source without primary source citation')
(776, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 'Related Info', 'Archaeological studies have demonstrated that sunflowers [including a variety of Helianthus spp.] were either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" as a food resource by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana', 'Bush 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 2, 'Bush 2003')
(777, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo0MzU5Nzoy', 'Use - Food', 'flowers, flower buds or petals fried and eaten. Buds eaten raw as a snack', 'Tippman and Swenda 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman and Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005')
(778, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyMDAxMjoy', 'Use - Customs/Medicinal', 'the chief smokes a sick person for healing. \"the smoking ceremony we think it kind of purifies us . . . If you\'re sick or anything the chief will come out and smoke you which we feel like it helps you get well . . .we use to make the smoke is cedar and cedar is a cleanser . . green cedar to get more smoke, we use tobacco, tobacco is a purifier and then we use sage and its for medicinal [purposes] . . . there was some sweetgrass mixed with the combination of sage and tobacco uh and the cedar\"', 'Wade 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Chuck Wade by Brant Hall, MTO Headquarters, Miami, OK, 6/21/99, MTO Archives')
(779, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyMDAxMjoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'component of medicine bag. \". . . cedar is like a purification, um, the sweet grass . . . corn all of those have a something, I\'m not sure what they all are. Its just medicine. Everything you would need to sustain you here or here after, is that little tiny portion, is in that bag\"', 'Mullin 1996', '1996', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Barbara Mullin, Carlson 1996')
(780, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyMDAxMjoy', 'Use - Customs', 'current Nation drum has tobacco and sweetgrass tied all around the Nation drum. Gary\'s personal habit is to tie a sweetgrass turtle to drum. Use of sweetgrass with drum learned from the Ojibway', 'Shoemaker', '2004', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Gary Shoemaker, 2004')
(781, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyMDAxMjoy', 'Use - Customs', 'used for smoking, like cedar. \". . that\'s the only thing she ever used it for, kind of a purifying, just like we used cedar\" \". . . it was just loose and she\'d just tied a string around it. I didn\'t see any in Oklahoma. She got that whenever she came back here [Indiana]. If they came back here to visit or something why then she\'d come back with some of that. And she would just . . .set it on the stove sometimes, you know, we had a wood stove and she\'d put it on the top of that like she did cedar. And I guess it was medicine as far as it purified the air and everything. It made a smoke. Yeah, just like the cedar does\"', 'Walker, Olds, Olds, Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds, and Tippman 1999')
(782, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyMDAxMjoy', 'Horticultural Info', 'The sweet grass with the red stem was preferred', 'Walker, Olds, Olds, Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds, and Tippman 1999')
(783, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyMDAxMjoy', 'Related Info', 'Only two plants, wild tobacco and red cedar, were used traditionally as ceremonial plants by the Miami. Contemporary uses of other plants in ceremonies, including white sage (Salvia apiana, from western U.S.) and sweetgrass (Hierochloe odorata) have been acquired often from the pan-Indian movement of modern times', 'Gonella 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s note and pers. comm. with Baldwin 2005')
(784, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo3MjEyNzoy', 'Habitat', 'A native weedy species occurring in moist areas including oldfields, pastures, other human-disturbed areas', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991, Small 1903')
(785, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo3MjEyNzoy', 'Related Info', 'A relative of the cultivated barley (H. vulgare), Little barley is extremely abundant in some areas', 'Thieret 2001', '2001', '', '', 0, 0, 'Thieret 2001')
(786, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo3MjEyNzoy', 'Related Info', 'Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that Little barley was either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" by indigenous peoples during the Late Woodland period (prior to 700 A.D. through 1450 A.D.)', 'Bush 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 0, 'Bush 2003')
(787, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo5MTA4MDoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in rich, deep woods', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(788, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo5MTA4MDoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'root dried and pounded into a powder was used to relieve pain and heal membranes and cuts', 'Rafert 1992', '1992', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interviews with Miami elders 1977-1992, Rafert 1992:45')
(789, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo5MTA4MDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'collected and dried, then sold for pharmaceutical use', 'Rafert 1996', '1996', '', '', 0, 0, 'Rafert 1996:182')
(790, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo5MTA4MDoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'carefully used as an unspecified medicine, with the potential to cause abortion', 'Walker, Olds, Olds, Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds, and Tippman 1999')
(791, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToxOTMxOjI=', 'Related Info', 'See \"mic8kinamagane\" record, which may be referring to jewelweed', '', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s note')
(792, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo4OTM0NDoy', 'Use - Food', 'eaten. \"Kekanwa kuthiaki\", or \"kinwa kussia\" or \"paxkussia\" are the old Miami language terms for wild potatoes, also called batate. Now the shortened term \'kussia\' is used for commercial sweet potatoes', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:756 & 1753')
(793, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo4OTM0NDoy', 'Use - Food', 'eaten. \"wawikapakosia, sweet potato\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:4734-35dw')
(794, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo4OTM0NDoy', 'Related Info', 'Sweet potatoes a traditional food', 'Myaamiaki 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 2, 'Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 2(2):12, 1999')
(795, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo4OTM0NDoy', 'Related Info', 'Checked in Small\'s Flora of the Southeastern U.S., Gleason and Cronquist, and Coulter\'s Flowering Plants and Ferns of Indiana, none of which mention a \'sweet potato\' in the index or within the potato family, nor a \'batate\' in the index', '', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Small 1903; Gleason and Cronquist 1991; Coulter 1899')
(796, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Habitat', 'Ipomaea pandurata: dry woods and thickets; Helianthus tuberosus: moist soils and waste places', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(797, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'tubers eaten. [Perrot\'s \"Indian potatoes\" probably refers to this species or Jerusalem artichoke]', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 0, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Dunn 1919')
(798, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'gathered in wet prairies and eaten. \"paneekee, wild potato, these are found in abundance in the wet prairies throughout the country and are gathered in hoeing time (June). They are easily boiled and when they wish to change the color the Indians throw a few leaves of the soft maple [into the cooking kettle] which turns them black\"', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:64-65')
(799, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'waupeeseepina is the white potato, found growing in low prairies and the potatoe portion similar in appearance and taste to the commericial potato of the times (ca. 1938). Easily cooked and very good tasting, these roots are used much by the Miami, particularly when food is seasonally scarce.', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65')
(800, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'wild potatoes are gathered in prairies, cooked and eaten. \"pa\'na, pena . . . Refers to one or more species of onion-like or turnip-shaped nutritious bulbs growing extensively upon the western prairies. This \"pomme blanche\" as named by the \"coureurs des bois\" look dark and are sweeter than our Irish potatoes. They cook in six hours and are usually called by these Indians [the Miami] nalauxki pa\'naki\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1809')
(801, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'the archaic term for this [sweet potato] fruit is kinwa kussia, pl. kinwa(ki) kussiaki \"long potato.\" The archaic term is still used by many people', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895')
(802, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'kenkanwa kuthiaki sweet potatoes, archaic for batates, now kussia', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895')
(803, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Use - Food', 'paxkussia, kussia /-aki pl. sweet potato, better called batate. The archaic name given to this fruit is kinwa kussia long fruit', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895')
(804, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Horticultural Info', 'nimic8ah8aki = \"I found some roots, potatoes, for example digging with a stick etc.\"', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca.1700:295.15')
(805, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Related Info', 'The Miami-Illinois term \"panick\" means potatoes, \"paniki axki\" means potato field and \"ahpeniikiinsa\" means little potatoes. Ts [000] recorded the term \"paanarkee\" as indicating potato in Miami-Illinois', 'Kerr 1835', '1835', '', '', 0, 2, 'Kerr 1835:359, 1st Wea Primer, from Mongosa; Gatschet ca. 1895:69; Dunn ca. 1900:3788dw; ts000')
(806, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Related Info', 'The Miami term \"ahpena\" means the cultivated, domesticated garden potato, Solanum tuberosum in contemporary times, but originally used for another edible tuber', 'Gonella', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s note')
(807, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 'Related Info', 'According to the University of Michigan at Dearborn, Native American Ethnobotany Database (Moerman), Ipomoea pandurata is widely used by indigenous groups across North America, with most uses being medicinal, and only two records, one by the Cherokee, as a food/starvation food source. This species is the best guess at what was harvested in the summer (not oonsaapeekatiki, since this is a fall/winter/early spring harvest) and considered \'ahpena\'', 'Gonella', '2006', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s note, 5.6.06')
(808, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNjkyNzoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in marshes, swamps, meadows and shores', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(809, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNjkyNzoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'roots chewed as a remedy for mouth sores', 'Rafert 1992', '1992', '', '', 0, 0, 'Rafert 1992:43, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy')
(810, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjozMTIyNToy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in moist soils or swamps and waste places', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Small 1903; Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(811, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjozMTIyNToy', 'Related Info', 'Archaeological studies have demonstrated that sumpweed was either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" as a food resource by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana. Remains of seeds of sumpweed do not appear again after 700 A.D. in Indiana archaeological sites', 'Bush 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 2, 'Bush 2003')
(812, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjozMjQyNDoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in rich woods, especially on calcareous soils', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(813, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjozMjQyNDoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'part of recipe for rheumatism. \". . . A quart of whiskey two handfuls red pepper two oz casteel soap half oz salt hartshorn the same of laudnaum and as much jimweed or L. rheumatism root as some term it as you can hold in your hand. Bruise and boil it in a quart water until it is bitter. The stronger the better. Strain it and add the ingredients. Stew them till soft and bottle for use. While using the above, ironweed tea or bitters to cleans the blood\"', 'Hackley', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Hackley, year unknown')
(814, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNTA2Nzoy', 'Description', '\"Butternut has a shell that looks something like a walnut but they\'re smaller . . .They\'re long, almost twice as long as a walnut . . They\'re oblong\"', 'Strack 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(815, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNTA2Nzoy', 'Habitat', 'rich, moist soils throughout eastern and western Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(816, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNTA2Nzoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"sinkisisa, butternut tree\"', 'Hockett 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 0, 'Hockett 1938:043')
(817, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNTA2Nzoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"kinoci\'ci, butternut tree\"', 'Dunn ca. 1900', 'ca. 1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:943dw')
(818, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNTA2Nzoy', 'Use - Food', 'nuts gathered for food', 'Tippmann 1999', '1999', 'nuts eaten', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(819, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNTA2Nzoy', 'Use - Material', 'Human-charred butternut/walnut timbers were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River', 'Bush 1996', '1996', 'used in construction', '', 0, 0, 'Bush 1996:184')
