(912, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo2NzY4NDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'young shoots of hackberry, elm and poplar fed to livestock during hard times', 'Peckham 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938; possibly another species in populus genus, or yellow poplar, Liriodendron tulipifera')
(913, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo2NzY4NDoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"mal\'lusandia\", white poplar', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895')
(914, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo2NzY4NDoy', 'Use - Customs', 'poplar may have been the \"tree of peace\" mentioned by a Piankeshaw Chief in a meeting with Thomas Dalton in 1784, receiving a peace belt from the white men and hoping to reciprocate and form a more peaceful relationship; \"We thus plant the tree of peace, that God may spread branches; so that we call all be secured from bad weather\"', 'Filson 1793', '1793', '', '', 0, 0, 'Filson 1793:79-83')
(915, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo2NzY4NDoy', 'Related Info', 'Cultural use references referring to white poplar indicated the yellow poplar (Liriodendron tulipifera), as deduced by fact that the yellow poplar has been called White poplar because of its light and easily worked wood, and because the introduced White poplar (Populus alba) was not introduced until 1748, nor widespread before the 19th century, whereas traditions relating to peace were probably established long before this time', 'Gonella', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s note')
