(1386, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2ODAwMDoy', 'Habitat', 'One or a number of Rumex species could be referred to by \"slick dock\". In general, docks grow in wet areas (moist soils, wetland edges, swamps) or disturbed sites', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1387, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2ODAwMDoy', 'Use - Food', 'young leaves called \"slick dock\" gathered and eaten as greens', 'Walker, Davis, Dagenet, Walker 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Howard Walker, Judy Davis, Ken Dagenet and Mildred Walker, Gonella 2004')
(1388, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2ODAwMDoy', 'Use - Food', 'young leaves of \"slick dock\" eaten as greens, but not leaves of curly dock (Rumex crispus). The \"slick dock\" they gathered had narrow, slick-looking (shiny) leaves [possibly the young leaves of various Rumex species: author\'s note] where the curly had wide, tough and curled-edge leaves', 'Walker 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mildred Walker, 2004, Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999')
(1389, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2ODAwMDoy', 'Use - Food', 'young leaves gathered and cooked as greens. \" It was used as a spring tonic for cleansing the body. The young leaves of poke, curly dock and lamb\'s quarter\'s were gathered near my house, mixed together and cooked with vinegar\"', 'Davis 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Judy Davis, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/1/04')
