(1403, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"nipiakki, willow (generic of kinds of willows growing along streams\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:5377dw')
(1404, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Material', 'willow boughs used to made wiikiaami, at 2nd annual language camp in Sunnyside, WA, held by Sammye Darling', 'Myaamiaki 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 2(2):12, 1999')
(1405, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Material', 'used for bulding wikiamis. \". . . yellow willow best for wiikiaami, bends very well but hard to find now, not as much as there used to be . . .other willows good too. It seems to absorb the moisture when wet and last longer.\"', 'Shoemaker 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Gary Shoemaker, 2003')
(1406, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"nipiaxkawi (weeping) willow, generic term comprehending the willows growing near the water, same as nipiaxkwa\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1639')
(1407, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NzQ3Nzoy', 'Related Info', 'material use: Peoria observation of Nez Perces when they were held in Miami--\"They made a basket out of buck-husk and willow weeds, also large carved wooden jars and much beadwork.\"', 'Peckham 1938', '1938', '', '', 0, 2, 'Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938')
(1408, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NzQ3Nzoy', 'Related Info', 'The \'nip\' stem of the Miami word \'nipiaahkwi\' probably refers to a number of willow species that grow along watercourses and in moist areas', 'Baldwin', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Note from Daryl Baldwin')
(1409, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NzQ3Nzoy', 'Related Info', 'material use: fibers from the black willow (Salix nigra) use to make bags, pouches, fish nets, and cordage by Menomini, Winnebago, Michigan Ottawa, and Ojibway Indians. To prepare the black willow fiber, the bark was stripped from the tree, then the inner white bast tissue removed, boiled, pounded and rubbed until the fibers were loosened for twisting. All specimens contain prepared fibers', 'Whitford 1941', '1941', '', '', 0, 2, 'Whitford 1941')
(1410, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NDI1NToy', 'Habitat', 'Native to arid and semi-arid areas of western U.S.', '', '', '', '', 0, 1, 'Unknown source list')
(1411, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NDI1NToy', 'Use - Customs/Medicinal', 'the chief smokes a sick person for healing. \"the smoking ceremony we think it kind of purifies us . . . If you\'re sick or anything the chief will come out and smoke you which we feel like it helps you get well . . .we use to make the smoke is cedar and cedar is a cleanser . . green cedar to get more smoke, we use tobacco, tobacco is a purifier and then we use sage and its for medicinal [probably white sage, currently used by many tribes for similar purposes] . . . there was some sweetgrass mixed with the combination of sage and tobacco uh and the cedar\"', 'Wade 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Chuck Wade by Brant Hall, MTO Headquarters, Miami, OK, 6/21/99, MTO Archives')
(1412, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NDI1NToy', 'Use - Food', 'hung dry and possibly used for cooking', 'Walker, Olds, Olds, Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999')
(1413, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NDI1NToy', 'Related Info', 'Only two plants, wild tobacco and red cedar, were used traditionally as ceremonial plants by the Miami. Contemporary uses of other plants in ceremonies, including white sage (Salvia apiana, from western U.S.) and sweetgrass (Hierochloe odorata) have been acquired often from the pan-Indian movement of modern times', 'Gonella 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s note and pers. comm. with Baldwin 2005')
(1414, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Habitat', 'S. canadensis occurs in moist or rich woods, fields, and roadsides in eastern and western Miami lands, while S. racemosa occurs in rich woods in only eastern Miami territory', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1415, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"wikullumpsa\", or wiikooloomphsa, \"elder bush\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900, Eastern Miami')
(1416, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Food', 'berries gathered and made into juice', 'Walker, Olds, Olds, Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999')
(1417, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Food', 'berries gathered for making into preserves, sometimes mixed with something else to make more tart', 'Strackman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(1418, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Material', 'stems hollowed out using a willow branch, then a whittled down hickory stick placed inside along with a paper wad to make a \'pop-gun\'', 'Strackman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(1419, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"papikwa\'nze, papikweze, elder-tree, probably Sambucus glauca. SW [Sarah Wadsworth] thinks the pit in it named the tree papikwanshi-wanshi is pith or marrow\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1896')
(1420, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Food', 'berries made into jelly, flower buds and heads can be deep fried and eaten', 'Swenda 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mary (Strack) Swenda, Gonella 2005')
(1421, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Technology', 'stem hollowed out and used as a tap for maple sugaring', 'Swenda 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mary (Strack) Swenda, Gonella 2005')
(1422, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Use - Food', 'wild elderberries picked and eaten as a child. Mother, Thelma Louise Baker of the Eagle Band, made elderberry wine and jelly', 'Dorin 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with George Dorin, Gonella 2005')
(1423, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Related Info', 'Flowers of Sambucus canadensis or S. nigra contain volatile oils, resins and other compounds that when given in small doses (4 gm) act as a diaphoretic, diuretic, and stimulant, and are used to treat erysipelas, and fevers', 'Coulter 1932', '1932', '', '', 0, 2, 'Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.')
(1424, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 'Related Info', 'An undetermined source listed \"kilu..sah\" for \'alders\' and another unlisted source listed \"peekatami$i, pacottameiz\" for \"alder bushes\"', 'Language Database 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 2, 'Language database, 2004')
(1425, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTozMjc4MDoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs on rich, moist soil throughout eastern and western Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1426, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTozMjc4MDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'used to make yellow paint. \"onzalamoni, bloodroot, i.e. yellow paint\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(1427, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTozMjc4MDoy', 'Use - Technology', '(trade) collected and dried, then sold for pharmaceutical use', 'Rafert 1992', '1992', '', '', 0, 0, 'Rafert 1992:182')
(1428, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTozMjc4MDoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'used as a tonic', 'Marks 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:104')
(1429, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTozMjc4MDoy', 'Related Info', 'emetic, purgative and yellow paint', 'Peterson', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Peterson\'s guide (date unknown)')
(1430, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Description', 'Also known as \"Ague Tree\"', 'Small 1903', '1903', '', '', 0, 0, 'Small 1903')
(1431, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in disturbed woods, thickets, roadsides and oldfields', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1432, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Habitat', 'Occurred in many places, especially along railroad tracks', 'Strack 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 1, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(1433, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'root used for drink/tea. \"mangi\' cakwi\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(1434, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'leaves made into tea for a spring tonic. Barbara Mullin\'s grandparents, both sets, including Ethel Goodbo Gamble, believed in the health-inducing properties of sassafras tea, drunken as a spring tonic. Barbara said, \"My grandfather said on the first day of February that you had to have a cup of sassafras every day through the month of February and then you would not be ill all year . . . And he lived to be 93.\" Her brother-in-law owns several trees and gets the roots for selling. She goes out every year to collect the roots, except this last year. \"We always knew what it looked like, at that state [without leaves]. It has a certain smell . . . You can tell.\" They would cut the gathered roots into small segments and boil. Patches need to be identified in the summer, so they could return in the winter to the right place\"', 'Mullin 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Barbara Mullin, Gonella 2003')
(1435, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'sassafras tea was considered a tonic. \"And sassafras, of course, has always been known since the earliest days of this country, in the Middle West and all the way to the coast of South Carolina.\"', 'Marks 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989')
(1436, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'sassafras tea made from root and used as a blood thinner/conditioner', 'Miami elders 1992', '1992', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Miami elders, Rafert 1992:45')
(1437, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'tea made', 'Walker, Olds, Olds, Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999')
(1438, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'used roots to make tea', 'Strack 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(1439, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'root used to prevent bleeding, the pith used in treating sore eyes, and tea used in spring. \"the pulverized root is an aboriginal remedy against bleeding, its pith is helpful fore sore eyes, it is drank in spring time as we drink tea or coffee. Being considered as the best blood purifier it was called medicine bush. Sassafras officinale, it belongs to the family of the laurineae and is a native of the united states. As it furnishes one of the most important remedies to the Indians, they call it for short the medicine tree, either m., or m. tawani. They drink the decoction of the root, m. tchipki chiefly in spring time as a drug as tea and as an every day beverage and regard it as the best blood purifier. The pulverized root is their remedy against bleeding, its pith is helpful for soreness of the eyes\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1052')
(1440, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'roots harvested for making tea. \"The tea is good all year long, but especially in the spring when you get fresh root.\" For storage can make shavings and dry.', 'Tippman and Swenda 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman and Mary (Strack) Swenda, Gonella 2005')
(1441, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'roots dug up, sliced, boiled and steeped in water to make tea. Honey added for taste. Used in the longhouse during a sweat', 'Dorin 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with George Dorin, Gonella 2005')
(1442, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"makinjak8i\", sassafras', 'Pinet 1969-1700', '1969-1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pinet 1696-ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117')
(1443, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Horticultural Info', 'Collect roots in January. \"You need to know what it looks like without leaves. . . it has a certain smell, . . . you can tell. Pull up small trees and get roots. You have to go to different patches [so you don\'t kill all the trees in one patch].\"', 'Mullin 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Barbara Mullin, Gonella 2003')
(1444, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Horticultural Info', 'Collect roots in early spring. Tie a ribbon to stems in the fall to remember which stems to dig up. The cut roots resprout usually', 'Tippman 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman, Gonelal 2004')
(1445, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Horticultural Info', 'Smaller roots (1/2 to 2 inches diameter) harvested in fall, around the end of October, when the sap is down, always offering tobacco as he harvests. Once he harvested a 3-4\" diameter root, but only took the top half of the root, and left the bottom intact so the root could still grow. He covered the exposed portion of the root with sassafras bark and packed earth back around it', 'Dorin 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with George Dorin, Gonella 2005')
(1446, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Related Info', 'Barbara Mullin\'s recipe for sassafras tea: boil a few pieces of sassafras roots. Simmer for about 20 minutes until tea is clear and very bright pink/red. Add sugar or honey if desired. Serve hot', 'Myaamiaki 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 2, 'Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 2(3):14, 1999')
(1447, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Related Info', 'The Miami word \'mankii?aahkwaapowi\' means sassafras tea, and incorporates the Miami words for medicine, bush and drink', 'Myaamiaki 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 2, 'Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 2(3):14, 1999')
(1448, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Related Info', 'Sassafras jelly recipe from Barbara Mulllin, from a Choctaw, includes sassafras tea, honey, and sassafras root bark', 'Myaamiaki 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 2, 'Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 2(2):14, 1999')
(1449, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Related Info', 'Oil from roots are aromatics, stimulants, diaphoretic, diuretic, aseptic and astringent. This oil is used mostly as a flavor. Large doses causes circulatory depression and respiratory paralysis. Oil is reported to cause contraction of the uterus and abortion', 'Coulter 1932', '1932', '', '', 0, 2, 'Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.')
(1450, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Related Info', 'Due to lead, cadmium and zinc contamination in the Tar Creek Superfund Site\'s watershed, around Miami, Oklahoma and the Miami Tribe of Oklahoma\'s headquarters, Miami and other local tribal members worry that traditional gathering of food, medicine and customs items may be contaminated. Fish, wild blackberries, sassafras, pokeweed, basket-making supplies and wild onions could have high concentrations of lead, as do the waters of nearby lakes, and it is not always successful keeping tribal members out of these areas. The Seneca-Cayuga\'s berry dance could not be held, if all the wild blackberries and strawberries in the area are found to be contaminated', 'Tulsa World 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 2, 'Tulsa World 7/13/2003')
(1451, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Related Info', 'Charlevoix describes use of tree sap and sassafras against palsy, dropsy and venereal diseases, by the general Great Lakes region tribes', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 2, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:174, from Kellogg 1923:161-162')
(1452, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 'Related Info', '\"Recurring ague and fever however, was a condition affecting the lands in the Miami Tribe claim as of the dates of this appraisal\" --possibly the \"ague\" tree was used in the treatment of diseases like malaria', 'Hoyt 1959', '1959', '', '', 0, 2, 'Hoyt 1959:121')
(1453, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in marshes and muddy shores of lakes and streams, tolerant of alkalai', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1454, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in marshes', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 1, 'Pease 1934:316, Deliette 1721')
(1455, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'long mats or smaller mats, to be used as bed mats, approximately the size of settler\'s beds circa 1895. When to be used as a bed mat, it is our size of beds and laid on the ground\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1772')
(1456, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'bed mat that is the length and width of settler\'s beds circa 1909, and is laid bare on the ground', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria')
(1457, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'mats made from rushes. \"At night most of the men, seated like dogs on mats of round reeds, play with straws\"', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:351, \"et la nuit comme des Chiens la plus part assis sur des nattes de joncs ronds jouent avec des pailles,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(1458, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'rush mat used for dancing upon during peace-making ceremony', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:28')
(1459, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'women are in charge of making the mats', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:46')
(1460, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'pre-war singing. \"they invite them to a feast and tell them that the time is approaching to go in search of men, so it is well to pay homage, according to their custom, to their birds so that these may be favorable. They all answer with a loud Ho! And after eating with great appetite they all go get their mats and spread out their birds on a skin stretched in the midle of the cabin and with the chichicoyas they sing a whole night . . . \"', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:376, \"ils les invitent dans un festin Et leur disent comme Voila Le temps qui approche pour aller chercher des hommes il est bon de rendre les devoirs selon leur Coutume a leurs oyseaux afin qu\'ils leurs soient favorables, Ils repondent tous par un grand ho, Et apres avoir mange d\'un grand appetit, ils Vont querir chacun Leur nattes etendent tous Leurs oyseaux dessus une peau qui est estendue au milieu de la Cabane Et avec des Chichicoya chante une nuit entiere,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(1461, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'mat made of softstem bullrush used as a bundle for carrying herbal medicines to cure those wounded in war. \"the commander carries his mat, into which all his men have put their birds, along with a good stock of herbs for healing the wounded\"', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:379, \"Le Commandant porte sa Natte dans laquelle tout son monde a mis ses oyseaux, ou il y a bonne provision d\'herbes pour panser Les Blessez,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(1462, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'they sit on their mats during a healing ceremony, put on by the medicine men and women, to instill belief in their powers among the young', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:369-371; \"Ils ont aussi une maniere Extraordinaire et ridicule pour faire croire leurs remedes Infaillibles qui ne laisse pas de faire sur l\'esprit de la Jeunesse L\'Effet qu\'ils demandent. Deux out trois fois dans L\'Ete, dans la plus belle place de leur Village, ils font planter des perches en terre, d\'un demy arpent en quarre en maniere d\'enclos, Laquelle ils garnissent de nattes au tour,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(1463, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'used to make mats for sitting on. \" Every young man has a little mat made of the round reeds I have mentioned which grow in the marshes. The women dye them black, yellow and red and make them three feet long and two feet wide. They fold over one end about a foot in the form of a comb case and in which they put some of these birds of which I have spoken [i.e. war bundles]\"', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:375; \"Chaque Jeune homme a une petite natte qui est faite des plus Joncs ronds dont J\'ay parle qui Viennent dans les marais, Les femmes les teignent en noir, Jaune, et Rouge Et les font de trois pieds de Long et deux de Lage, ils en plient au bout d\'un pied de Long en forme d\'une trousse a mettre des peignes, c\'est dans quoy ils mettent quelques uns de ces oyseaux don’t Je viens de parler,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(1464, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'finely woven mats made. \"Their [the Illinois] Cabins are cover\'d with Mats of flat Rushes, so closely woven together, that no Wind, Rain, or Snow can go thro\' it [153].\" \". . .the Illinois, make their Cabins of flat Rushes, which they sew together, and line them with the same. . . [167].\"', 'Hennepin 1698', '1698', '', '', 0, 0, 'Hennepin 1698, from Thwaites 1903:153 & 167')
(1465, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'during the summer months of cultivation, April through October, permanent villages were inhabited, and during this time women gathered wild foods and mat materials as well', 'La Salle 1679-1680', '1679-1680', '', '', 0, 0, 'La Salle 1679-1680, from Margry 1974:171')
(1466, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'coverings and floorings for dwellings. \"Their cabins are very large; they are made, cover\'d, and pav\'d with mats of marish [marsh]-rushes\"', 'Marquette 1673', '1673', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1673:210, from Thwaites 1903:652')
(1467, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Customs', 'Guests are given their finest mats on which to rest. \"A stranger as soon as he arrives [at a cabin--Blair\'s brackets] is made to sit down on a mat, of the handsomeest, in order to rest from his fatigue . . .\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 0, 'Perrot 1680-1718, fro Blair 1911:132')
(1468, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'used for making long mats. \"lansuni, long mats are manufactured from a round stemmed scirpus-reed growing in the Indian territory\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895')
(1469, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Use - Material', 'The Peorias made a long mat, lasuni, from scirpus growing in these parts. One of these is a flat scirpus [probably cattail], pakwayaki \"used for roofs, thatching; the other round scirpus, lasonaki. This is a bed mat and is just the length and width of our beds; laid bare on the ground\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(1470, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Horticultural Info', '\". . . one of them went off three or four arpents into a hollow, which in spring is nothing but a sort of marsh and brought back a bundle of round reeds as thick as one fingers.\"', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:316; \"un d\'eux fut a 3. ou 4. arpents dans un fond ou le printemps ce n\'est qu\'une maniere de marais, et apporterent une botte de Roseaux ronds qui sont gros comme les doigts,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(1471, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Related Info', 'The word \'mizanikani\' means fabric, straw, or any other rushes (Scirpus spp.) that were used for the purposes listed', 'Gonella', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gonella\'s notes')
(1472, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Related Info', 'There is a coiled basket that is possibly made of softstem bullrush, housed at the National Museum of the American Indian, in Washington D.C.', '', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Unknown source list')
(1473, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Algonquian women, in general, made the mats for roofing or flooring of dwellings. They also carried these mats when they traveled by foot. \"The obligations of women are to . . .make . . . mats of rushes (either flat or round, or long) to serve as roofing for the cabins or as mattresses. . . . When they are traveling, the women carry the roofing for the cabin, if there is no canoe.', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:75-76')
(1474, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Related Info', 'Upon the death of a man\'s brother Algonquians, neighbors to the surviving brother offer the deceased two gifts in order to remove the tears of his relatives; a mat to lie on and a piece of bark to shelter the corpse from the weather. \"In the speech which they [neighbors] accompany this gift they declare that it is made in order to wipe away the tears of his relatives; and that the mat which they give him is for him to lie on, or [that they give--Blair\'s note] a piece of bark to shelter his corpse from the injurious effects of the weather\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:80')
(1475, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 'Related Info', 'The Miami-Illinois term \"keentowasiki\" is used generally for rush, or bulrush. Gatschet notes that it is probably an adjective word, meaning \"sharp-cutting\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 2, 'Gatschet ca. 1895')
(1476, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NDk1NDoy', 'Habitat', 'S. obtusifolia is a native species that is now pantropical and found in moist woods in eastern and western Miami lands, and S. occidentalis is a native of the Old World tropics but naturalized in eastern and western Miami lands in sandy and alluvial soils along streams and disturbed areas', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991, Steyermark 1963')
(1477, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NDk1NDoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'leaves made into laxative. Sugar balls infused with senna, in center, recipe by Effie Louella (pimyotahmah) Walker Brown', 'Myaamiaki 2002', '2002', '', '', 0, 0, 'Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 5(2):10, 2002')
(1478, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NDk1NDoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'senna balls rolled in sugar eaten for strengthening the blood but too much could cause diarrhea', 'Beam 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Letha Beam, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, June 6, 2003')
(1479, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NDk1NDoy', 'Related Info', 'Referring to cultural use as a laxative by Effie--in same discussion, Watona relayed that in the Miami tradition, medicinal knowledge was passed on orally to the opposite sex child, therefore Effie and great aunt Myrtle Walker Fuller (shegoquah) were not taught the medicinal knowledge of their mother, Rebecca Stitt (Pimyotomah) Walker, a well know mid-wife and medicine woman in Lincolnville, OK at the turn of the century. Rebecca was the daughter of Mary Benjamin Stitt (Kepahkakasequah, who was relocated from Indiana to Kansas. Effie and her sister reportedly learned Miami herbal medicine by sneaking around the woods as Rebecca foraged teaching her sons', 'Myaamiaki 2002', '2002', '', '', 0, 2, 'Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 5(2):10, 2002')
(1480, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NDk1NDoy', 'Related Info', 'Dried leaflets, in small doses (2 gm) has physiological action as a laxative, purgative, and cholagogue, also increasing the flow of bile', '', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'Unknown source list')
(1481, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NDk1NDoy', 'Related Info', 'Leaves of Senna obtusifolia are believed to possess the purgative qualities that are associated with the pharmaceutical drug \'senna\', and leaves of Senna occidentalis are used to make an ointment used as a remedy for ringworm and other skin problems', 'Steyermark 1963', '1963', '', '', 0, 2, 'Steyermark 1963:875')
(1482, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NDk2OToy', 'Use - Food', 'modern traditional crop. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909')
(1483, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDMyODoy', 'Habitat', 'Common species often occur in opening in woods, prairies, oldfields, meadows and disturbed areas', 'Gonella', '', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gonella\'s note')
(1484, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDMyODoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'tea made for unspecified purpose. Leaves gathered and dried, before it budded or bloomed', 'Walker, Olds, Olds, Tippman 1999', '19993', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999')
(1485, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2MzE1Mjoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in swamps, and on moist low ground in eastern Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1486, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2MzE1Mjoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"the Miamis use cikakwai\'nji for the skunk cabbage, or swamp cabbage, Symplocarpus foetidus\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(1487, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2MzE1Mjoy', 'Use - Food', 'boiled and eaten as greens, \"at the right stage when it first came up.\" It was still eaten by tribal members and others he knew when he was a young man and even at the time of the interview', 'Marks 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:91-92')
(1488, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2MzE1Mjoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"chingishimintchi\"', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca. 1700')
(1489, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2MzE1Mjoy', 'Use - Food', 'gathered, cooked and eaten', 'Tippman 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman, Gonella 2005')
(1490, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2MzE1Mjoy', 'Related Info', 'McPherson wrote, \"The Indians [undescribed tribe] left the roots in pits with hot coals for two to three days before eating them.\"', 'McPherson 1977', '1977', '', '', 0, 2, 'McPherson 1977:40, 2ndy source without primary source citation')
(1491, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNToxNDAwOToy', 'Habitat', 'Eastern tansy, T. huronense is a native, occuring in riverbanks and shores in eastern Miami lands (Common tansy, T. vulgare, is an introduced species occuring in roadsides, fields and other disturbed areas throughout eastern and western Miami lands)', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1492, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNToxNDAwOToy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'leaves chewed or made into tea for what was called \"summer complaint\" or \"chills and fevers\"', 'Miami elders 1992', '1992', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interviews with Miami elders, Rafert 1992:45')
(1493, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNToxNDAwOToy', 'Related Info', 'Translation from Miami-Illinois means \'flying squirrel\'s tail\'', 'Costa 2003', '2003', '', '--descriptive category--morphologcal', 0, 2, 'Costa 2003, email')
(1494, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2MzgxOToy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in lawns and other disturbed areas throughout eastern and western Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1495, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2MzgxOToy', 'Use - Food', 'greens canned', 'Hunter and Bossley 1978', '1978', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Swan Hunter and Eva Bossley, Rafert 1978')
(1496, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2MzgxOToy', 'Use - Food', '\"Before the white people came here, they was no dandelions. Dandelions were imported. But once they became acquainted with the dandelions, they used them quite a bit.\"', 'Marks 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989')
(1497, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2MzgxOToy', 'Use - Food', 'leaves eaten as greens', 'Walker, Olds, Olds, Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999')
(1498, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2MzgxOToy', 'Use - Food', 'plants gathered. \"[We] had a line of catalpa trees. And so then they\'d [the older Indian women from the Catholic church near Mildred\'s home, growing up in Miami] set down with a knife and try to cut out the dandelions\"', 'Walker, Olds, Olds, Tippman 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999')
(1499, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2MzgxOToy', 'Use - Food', 'leaves picked and blanched, not cooked, and vinegar added and sometimes garlic for flavoring. \"Anything to make them a little different so you didn\'t think you were eating grass\"', 'Strack 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(1500, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2MzgxOToy', 'Use - Unknown', '', 'Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 0, 'Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content')
(1501, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2MzgxOToy', 'Use - Food', 'young leaves collected and eaten. Cooked with bacon drippings in past, or just boiled with butter and salt. Also eaten raw in a salad', 'Tippman, Swenda, Tippman 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman, Mary (Strack) Swenda and Mary Tippman, Gonella 2005')
(1502, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MzUyMjoy', 'Habitat', '\". . . you find them in the the woodlands. The first of all the flowering plants that grows in the woods is the turkey pea . . . \"', 'Marks 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 1, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989')
(1503, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MzUyMjoy', 'Use - Food', 'tuber eaten, \"And the way they found out they were good to eat--originally, what the story goes--is that the wild turkey nebbed them up on the leaves in the early spring. And that little tiny potato, in finding what they were eating, they tasted \'em and found out that they were edible. It took a lot of \'em to sustain you, but they were edible, and good to eat raw. They taste much like eating a raw sweet potato. . . You find them in the woodlands. The first of all the flowering plants that grows in the woods is the turkey pea or the salt and pepper\"', 'Marks 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:98-99')
(1504, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo3NjI5MDoy', 'Description', 'Two species were commonly called white cedar, according to Small, including Thuja occidentalis, and Chamaecyparis thoides, also known as cypress, but is found predominately on the coastal plain', 'Small 1903', '1903', '', '', 0, 0, 'Small 1903, Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1505, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo3NjI5MDoy', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in moist soils and swamps in eastern Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1506, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo3NjI5MDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'used as a baseboard when hand-starting fires. \"One of the pieces of wood which they use to make a fire is of white cedar, which is the most combustible, a foot long more or less, according as they choose to make it, and as thick as two fingers. On one side, on the very edge, they make little holes, in which they make a notch. They put this bit of wood on some rotten wood or on some grass, dry and very fine, after taking care to crush it thoroughly in their hands. The other piece of wood is as thick as the little finger, it is a bit of a wood that has a black berry, which we call morette. When this wood is green it is very soft, and it is proportionately hard when it is dry. They shape the end to the size of the holes in the other piece of wood, into one of which they insert it, and by turning it in their hands without ceasing, they produce a sort of powder from which, after a very short time, one sees smoke issue, which shortly is converted into flame. This coming through the notch of which I have just spoken, falls on the rotten wood or dry grass, which is ignited\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:317-318, Deliette 1721; \"un de ces morceaux don’t on se sert pour faire du feu est de Cedre blanc qui est le plus combustible d\'un pied plus ou moins de long, selon celle qui\'ils veulent luy donner, de la largeur de deux doigts, ils font d\'un coste tout sur le bord de petits trous, ou ils font une coche, ils mettent ce morceau de bois sur du bois poury, ou sur de l\'herbe bien seche et bien fine, apres qu\'ils ont eu le soin de la bien ecraser dans leurs mains, l\'autre morceau de bois est gros comme le petit doigt, c\'est un brin d\'un bois qui rapporte une graine noire, que nous appellons de la morette, quand ce bois est vert il est fort foible, et a proportion dur quand il est sec, ils amenuisent le bout de la grosseur des Troux de l\'autre morceau de bois, dans un desquels ils le mettent, et en le tournant dans leurs mains sans relache, ils se fait une maniere de poussiere don’t on voit en tres peu de temps comme j\'ay deja dit, sortir de la fumee, et ensuite se convertir en feu, cela coulant par cette coche don’t je viens de parler, tombe sur ce bois pouris ou herbe seche qui se convertit en feu,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(1507, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo3NjI5MDoy', 'Related Info', 'Great Lakes tribes, in general, used the sap squeezed from the ends of well-boiled cedar branches for the treatment of blood in the stool]', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 2, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:174, from Kellogg 1923:162')
(1508, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Habitat', 'Found in rich woods throughout eastern and western Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1509, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'cordage from inner bark of \"linn\" tree. \"For temporary use this needed no preparation. When boys went hunting with men, it was their first work to get linn bark to hobble the horses, while the men hunted. When rope was wanted for permanent use, the women boiled this bark, and twisted or braided it while it was damp\", \"fresh inside bark was used\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(1510, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'rope, greater than 2 cm diameter was made from \"whitewood bark\" by a soldier staying in an Illinois encampment', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:351, \"elle etoit d\'ecorce de Bois blanc, traissee plus grosse que le poulce,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(1511, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'cordage for fishing nets made from nettles and wild hemp. The women gather, spin and twist lengths of cordage on their bare thighs. The cords used to draw these nets are made of the bark of basswood or leather. With these nets many fish and beaver are captured. They also fish with still lines up to 90 meters long [possibly of the same cordage material]', 'Raudot 1904', '1904', '', '', 0, 0, 'Raudot 1904:Letter 41; secondary source for Deliette 1721')
(1512, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Material', 'women \"gather reeds in which they sew a twine made of basswood to make a sort of straw mat which covers their cabins. Two, one over the other, shelters them from the greatest rain\"', 'Raudot 1904', '1904', '', '', 0, 0, 'Raudot 1904:Letter 59, secondary source for Deliette 1721')
(1513, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Material', 'bark peeled off trees and used to cover houses, using poles. \"There was a tree they called linn trees, they would peel the bark off them and cover their houses and tie \'em down with a pole. Buckskin type\"', 'Carver 1968', '1968', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Rose Carver by J.W. Tyner, Miami, OK, 9/9/1968, in MTO Archives')
(1514, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'bark used to make cordage. In a traditional story, Wissakatchakwa was telling an old man how to catch birds. \"Peel a bunch of basswood-bark off the trees. Then dive into the lake, and tie the basswood bark to their feet. And . . . Tie them to your belt.\" He did this, then told all the ducks, geese, swans, and brants they had to leave. They flew away and carried him with them, until the bark broke . . . \"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895, from the traditional story Wissakatchakwa, told by George Finely, in Peoria')
(1515, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Material', 'there are 2 items that are possibly made with plant fibers, which could include dogbane, nettles or basswood, among others, at the Cranbrook Institute in Michigan', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Unknown source list')
(1516, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'cordage made from inner bark. \"The lesser occupations of the women and what is their common employment in their cabbins, are the making of threat from the interior pellicles of the bark of a tree, called white-wood [basswood], which they manufacture nearly as we do hemp', 'Charlevoix 1682-1761', '1682-1761', '', '', 0, 0, 'Charlevoix 1682-1761:125, from Kellogg 1923:116')
(1517, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Medicinal', 'root used to treat burns. \"The root of the whitewood boiled for burns\"', 'Anonymous 1724', '1724', '', '', 0, 0, 'Anonymous 1724:164A, \"De la racine de bois blanc bouillee pur la Bruleur\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004; the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups')
(1518, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'bark used to make rope. Akwaanaapiikatoo, climb with a rope. \"I climb by means of a cord, a vine, a long strong cord of bark from white wood\"', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca. 1700:010.12; \"je monte par une corde, une vigne, une babiche longue et forte, de l\'ecorces de bois blanc\"')
(1519, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Technology', 'bark used, probably for rope. \"lania paxshakinanga wikapi-mizha, a man jerks off the bark from a linn-tree\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1760')
(1520, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Unknown', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Unknown source list (sl 000?:060, 001, tb.sw 000?:011, as.sw 000?:002)')
(1521, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"8akapimingi\", basswood', 'Pinet 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pinet ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117')
(1522, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Related Info', 'Fibers from this tree were the most commonly used by all Eastern North American Indians in the manufacturing of many items, including a Menomini bag using carefully prepared fibers, a Potawatomi bag, a Sauk and Fox bag, and Hopewell textiles. Basswood was used in an unprocessed form, where strips were cut from the fiberous bast, and in a highly processed state, where bast was thoroughly treated and spun into fine thread', 'Whitford 1941', '1941', '', '', 0, 2, 'Whitford 1941')
(1523, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Related Info', 'Twine made from \"white wood\", probably Basswood, was used to tie together reeds, about 10-12 bands of these twines at 6 inch intervals along the reeds, to make coverings for their \"cabins\" that were about 20 meters (\"10 fathoms\") in length. They call them apacoya, a word which serves not merely to designate these, but which is a generic term for all sorts of coverings. They use the same term for bark boards, and two of these apacoyas, one on top of the other, protect one from the rain as well as the best blanket. These are the cabins which they use in autumn and winter; even if they leave their canoes, the women carry these on their backs', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 2, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:340-341,\"quelques jours apres ces femmes qui restent s\'en vont dans des pirogues don\'t elles ont jusqu\'a trois dans chaques cabanes, couper des joncs don\'t ils Couvrent leurs Cabannes, ce sont de ceux qui croissent dans leurs marais qui apportent des quenouilles lesquelles pres avoir oste une peau qui envelope plusieurs brins ensembles ils les font secher au soleil et passent une ficelle qu\'ils font de bois Blanc de l\'un a l\'autre, a dix ou douze endroits de distance d\'environ demy pieds, ils en font qui ont jusqu\'a dix brasses de longueur, ils appellent cela apacoya, ce n\'est pas que ce mot servent seulement a cela, c\'est un mot qui est generique pour toutes sortes de couvertures, ils disent de mesme pour des planches, et deux de ces apacoya L\'un sur l\'autre, metent aussi bien a la pluye que la meilleure couverture, se sont les Cabanes dont ils se servent l\'automne et l\'hiver, quoy quils quittent leurs pirogues, les femmes les portent sur leurs dos,\"ranslation from French to English by Pease')
(1524, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 'Related Info', 'Algonquians play a game called crosse, played with a wooden ball and racket with a netted end, like a tennis racket. \"There is among them a certain game, called crosse, which has much likenes to our game of long tennis . . . You will see them all equipped with the crosse--which is a light club, having at one end a broad flat part that is netted like a racket [possibly dogbane, basswood, nettles, or another strong fiber\"', 'Perrot 1680-1718', '1680-1718', '', '', 0, 2, 'Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:93')
(1525, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjoxNzI1OjI=', 'Habitat', 'A native of Europe occurring in oldfields, roadsides and disturbed areas as an escape from cultivation', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1526, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjoxNzI1OjI=', 'Use - Unknown', 'this clover was planted', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(1527, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo1MzE5NDoy', 'Habitat', 'A native of Eurasia occurring in roadsides and disturbed areas as an escape from cultivation', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1528, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo1MzE5NDoy', 'Use - Unknown', '\"nasopaki, clover\" and \"nasopaki anewatungi, red [clover]\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900:1232-3dw')
(1529, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo1MzE5NDoy', 'Related Info', 'The word \'neehsopaki\' refers to both white clover and other clover species', 'Dunn 1909', '1909', '', '', 0, 2, 'Dunn ca. 1909')
(1530, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Habitat', 'Occurs in ponds, marshes, and many other wet areas throughout eastern and western Miami lands', 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991', '1991', '', '', 0, 1, 'Gleason and Cronquist 1991')
(1531, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Habitat', '\"Along any of the slower moving streams you\'d find the cattail. There were a lot of wetlands, a lot of \'em in this country, especially around old burns and where old villages had been. The cattail seed was carried in there by birds and flourished there\"', 'Marks 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 1, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989')
(1532, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'mats, roof thatching. \"The Peorias made a long mat, lasuni, from scirpus [sic] growing in these parts. One of these is a flat scirpus, pakwayaki, used for thatching lodges\"', 'Dunn 1900', '1900', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dunn ca. 1900')
(1533, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'mats made from cattail leaves are called \"lansuni\" and are used for covering lodges. \"these mats lansuni serve for thatching lodges. After made into mats, these are called lansuni\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1753')
(1534, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'used for making walls and roofs of cabins, easily carried in a bundle while hunting. \"As Bark for making cabins is scarce in this county, They use Rushes [sic]; these serve Them for making walls and Roofs, but do not afford them much protection against the winds, and still less against the rains when they fall abundantly. The Advantage of Cabins of this kind is, that they make packages of Them, and easily transport them wherever they wish, while they are hunting\"', 'Marquette 1673', '1673', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1673, from Thwaites 1966:103, \"Comme le Escorces a faire des Cabbanes sont rares en ce pays la, Ils se seruent de Joncs qui Leur tiennent lieu de murailles et de Couuertures, mais qui ne les deffendent pas beaucoup des vents, et bien moins des pluyes quand elles tombent en abondance. La Commodite de ces sortes de Cabbanes est qu\'ils Les mettent en pacquetz et les portent aisement ou ils veulent pendant Le temps de leur chasse,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites')
(1535, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'coverings for dwellings made from cattails. \"Some days after this [after the village sets out on the buffalo hunt, after hilling up their corn at the beginning of June] the women who remain go off in canoes, of which they have as many as three in each cabin, to cut reeds with which they cover their cabins. These are a kind that grow in their marshes. They procure bundles of them, which, after removing a skin that encloses several blades conjointly, they dry in the sun and tie together with twine which they make of white wood, with ten or twelve bands at intervals of about six inches. They make these up to ten fathoms [approximately 20 meters] in length. They call them apacoya, a word which serves not merely to designate these, but which is a generic term for all sorts of coverings. They use the same term for bark boards, and two of these apacoyas, one on top of the other, protect one from the rain as well as the best blanket. These are the cabins which they use in autumn and winter, even if they leave their canoes, the women carry these on their backs\"', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:340-341, \"quelques jours apres ces femmes qui restent s\'en vont dans des pirogues don\'t elles ont jusqu\'a trois dans chaques cabanes, couper des joncs don\'t ils Couvrent leurs Cabannes, ce sont de ceux qui croissent dans leurs marais qui apportent des quenouilles lesquelles pres avoir oste une peau qui envelope plusieurs brins ensembles ils les font secher au soleil et passent une ficelle qu\'ils font de bois Blanc de l\'un a l\'autre, a dix ou douze endroits de distance d\'environ demy pieds, ils en font qui ont jusqu\'a dix brasses de longueur, ils appellent cela apacoya, ce n\'est pas que ce mot servent seulement a cela, c\'est un mot qui est generique pour toutes sortes de couvertures, ils disent de mesme pour des planches, et deux de ces apacoya L\'un sur l\'autre, metent aussi bien a la pluye que la meilleure couverture, se sont les Cabanes dont ils se servent l\'automne et l\'hiver, quoy quils quittent leurs pirogues, les femmes les portent sur leurs dos,\"ranslation from French to English by Pease')
(1536, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Food', '\"They ate the cattail root, and the shoot. The shoot of the cattail mostly. The early shoots coming up, they ate \'em raw and they ate them cooked, both [including people of Marks\' generation],\" \"I suppose most of the people ate the cattail shoot as cooked. Although they can eat it raw. Its edible raw\"', 'Marks 1989', '1989', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:99')
(1537, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'to use, peel off leaves and split the thick base of the leaves widthwise and place either side on a sinew line and bend over so leaf hangs down for drying--water runs off. They are woven two ways: 1) around parallel stems with sinew or 2) leaves/stems woven for floor mat', 'Shoemaker and Shoemaker 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Gary and Scott Shoemaker, Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK,Gonella 6/6/03')
(1538, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'cabins are roofed and floored with mats of rushes [cattails]', 'Marquette 1674', '16674', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:343')
(1539, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Customs', 'large mats of rushes painted in various colors are spread under trees on which the calumet dance (tobacco pipe dance) is done', 'Marquette 1674', '16674', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:343')
(1540, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'coverings for dwellings. \"As the Rind of Birch-trees are scarce in this country, they are oblig\'d to make their cabins with rushes, which serve as well for covering the same, as for walls. It must be own\'d that these cabins are very convenient; for they take them down when they please, and carry them by small parcels wherever they will, without any trouble\"', 'Joliet 1674', '1674', '', '', 0, 0, 'Joliet 1674:201, from Thwaites 1903:641')
(1541, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Technology', 'mats for drying corn, at the end of July: \"After this, as soon as it has boiled for a few minutes, they spread it on reed mats, which they also make in the same manner as those that serve for their cabins.\"', 'Pease 1934', '1934', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pease 1934:344, Deliette 1721; \"apres quoy sitot qu\'il a bouilly un demy quart d\'heure, elles l\'etendent sur des nattes de jonc qu\'elles font aussi de la meme maniere, que ceux don’t elles se servent pour leurs Cabanes,\" translation from French to English by Pease')
(1542, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Food', 'roots eaten', 'Shoemaker 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Gary Shoemaker, Gonella 2004')
(1543, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Food', 'shoots eaten. Jim Strack never used it himself but heard some say the shoots could be eaten', 'Strack 1999', '1999', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999')
(1544, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'cabins made from double mats of rushes. \"The greater part of these tribes, and especially the Ilinois, with whom I have had intercourse, make their cabins of double mats of flat rushes sewed together\"', 'Membre 1680-1681', '1680-1681', '', '', 0, 0, 'Membre 1680-1681 regarding La Salle, from Shea 1903:155')
(1545, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material/Technology', 'used to make mats. \"pauhkwiiyuk, a mat\"', 'Trowbridge 1825', '1825', '', '', 0, 0, 'Trowbridge 1825')
(1546, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'women \"gather reeds in which they sew a twine made of basswood to make a sort of straw mat which covers their cabins. Two, one over the other, shelters them from the greatest rain\"', 'Deliette 1721', '1721', '', '', 0, 0, 'Deliette 1721, secondary source from Raudot 1904:Letter 59')
(1547, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'walls and roof of dwellings. \"As bark for making cabins is scarce in this country, they use rushes; these serve them for making walls and roofs [sic], but do not afford them much protection against the winds, and still less against the rains when they fall abundantly. The advantage of cabins of this kind is, that they make packages of them, and easily transport them wherever they wish, while they are hunting\"', 'Marquette 1673', '1673', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1673, from Thwaites 1966:103; \"Comme les Escorces a faire des Cabannes sont rares en ce pays la, Ils se seruent de Joncs qui Leur tiennent lieu de murailles et de Couuertures, mais qui ne les deffendent pas beaucoup des vents, et bien moins des pluyes quand elles tombent en abondance. La Commodite de ces sortes de Cabannes est qu\'ils Les mettent en pacquetz et les portent aisement ou ils veulent pendant Le temps de leur chase,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites')
(1548, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Customs', 'used as floor covering for a summer calumet dance, for peace, or uniting during time of war, or to honor a Nation or person, where the mats are placed in the shade in the middle of the dance area. \"A large mat of rushes, painted in various colors, is spread in the middle of the place, and serves as a carpet upon which to place with honor the God of the person who gives the Dance [see attachment]\"', 'Marquette 1673', '1673', '', '', 0, 0, 'Marquette 1673, from Thwaites 1966:133; \"on etend une grande natte de joncs peinte de diverses couleurs au milieu de la place; elle sert comme de tapis pour mettre dessus avec honneur le Dieu de celuy qui fait fait la Dance,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites')
(1549, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Material', 'coverings for dwellings. \" . . . the village of the Illinois, consisting of about 400 cabins cover\'d with rushes . . .\"', 'Joliet 1674', '1674', '', '', 0, 0, 'Joliet 1674:190, from Thwaites 1903:628')
(1550, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Food', 'root harvested in spring, dislodged by the foot, cooked or eaten raw', 'Tippman 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Dani Tippman, Gonella 2005')
(1551, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Food', 'green [female] flowers, early shoots, roots eaten', 'Dorin 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with George Dorin, 2004')
(1552, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Use - Customs', 'woven into mats for covering wikkiup', 'Dorin 2005', '2005', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with George Dorin, Gonella 2005')
(1553, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Horticultural Info', 'Collected in August, when leaves are longer, collect green', 'Shoemaker and Shoemaker 2003', '2003', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with Gary and Scott Shoemaker, and Phyllis Miley, Gonela 2003')
(1554, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 'Horticultural Info', 'In early spring, can harvest early shoots and cook like asparagus, \"very good, sweet\". Make sure to only get the shoots that are white with a green tip. In late spring can harvest roots, \"some as big as your wrist, long as your forearm\", cut up, fry, bake or eat raw. In winter roots can be dug up, \"but by then they\'re old and tend to be wormy\"', 'Dorin 2004', '2004', '', '', 0, 0, 'Interview with George Dorin, Gonella 2004')
