(1643, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzozOTQwOjI=', 'Use - Food', 'traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909')
(1644, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzozOTQwOjI=', 'Use - Food', '\"papakimina des alizes\" or \"papakiminja alizier\", blackhaw berries', 'Gravier 1700', '1700', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gravier ca. 1700:430')
(1645, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzozOTQwOjI=', 'Use - Food', 'fruits eaten. \"papakimini, papakimina, fruit or berry of the black haw, sweet tiny and of a black color, lit. flat berry, grows on holy bushes, blackhaw trees grow to a height of 15 to 20 feet\"', 'Gatschet 1895', '1895', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gatschet ca. 1895:1844, 1225')
(1646, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzozOTQwOjI=', 'Related Info', 'Dried bark of Viburnum opulus var. americanum, cramp bark, in small doses (1-3 gm) is an antispasmodic, astringent, diuretic, and a tonic and sedative for the uterus', 'Coulter 1932', '1932', '', '', 0, 2, 'Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.')
(1647, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzozOTQwOjI=', 'Related Info', 'Blackhaw usually indicates Viburnum, whereas redhaw, or hawthorn or even black hawthorn indicate Crategeus spp. Blackhaw uses included Cherokee (drug/root-bark), Delaware (drug/root-bark), Micmac (drug), and Meskwaki (food/berry)', '', '', '', '', 0, 2, 'reference information needed')
